<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Labor Conference to Address Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The 86th International Labor
Conference began here Tuesday with the abolition of extreme forms
of child labor as its immediate goal.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session, representatives from governments,
employers and trade unions greeted hundreds of marchers who have
crossed over 100 countries this year in a "Global March Against
Child Labor" to demonstrate their opposition to child labor.
</P>
<P>
"You are far from your homes, but you have a home here," said
Michel Hansenne, Director-General of the International Labor
Organization (ILO). "We are going to develop some tools which can
be used by everyone wishing to bring an end to child labor."
</P>
<P>
In order to change the situation that millions of children are
exposed daily to exploitation, risks of accident, diseases, and
deaths, Hansenne said, the ILO will try "to identify, confront and
eliminate without delay" the extreme forms of child labor at its
annual conference in Geneva on June 2-18.
</P>
<P>
Conference President Jean-Jacques Oechslin said that the
current conference would be devoted to finding ways to protect
child laborers.
</P>
<P>
"Children represent the most vulnerable segment of our
societies and we cannot tolerate their exploitation under any
pretext whatsoever," he added.
</P>
<P>
The ILO estimates that 250 million children at the age of
between 5 and 14 in the developing countries have to work full
time or part time, of whom 61 percent are in Asia, 32 percent in
Africa, and seven percent in Latin America.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
