<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexicans Multiply U.S. Sales of Heroin: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Mexican drug cartels are now
producing some of the world's most potent heroin and are seizing
control of a rapidly growing share of the U.S. heroin business,
said The Washington Post on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Mexican drug dealers were long regarded as
peddlers of cheap, low-grade heroin that accounted for only a tiny
portion of the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
"Mexico has become the second-largest source of heroin used in
the United States, and the purity of the Mexican-produced drug has
increased sixfold in the past two years in what U.S. law
enforcement and health authorities describe as alarming trends,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The changes are tied to an emerging alliance between a
Colombian heroin trafficking organization and Mexican drug
smuggling groups that are learning how to produce more potent
heroin.
</P>
<P>
The largest evidence of the new alliance emerged in October
when Mexican officials arrested two Colombians and a Mexican near
the North Mexican town of Durango.
</P>
<P>
In a dramatic shift, Colombian and Mexican drug cartels largely
have taken over distribution in the U.S. from Asian organizations,
whose share of the American market has plunged from 90 percent to
28 percent since 1992, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted U.S. officials as saying that the shift in the heroin
supply coincides with a disturbing turn in drug consumption in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The number of heroin users has risen from 500,000 to 600,000
over the past two years while that of cocaine users has dropped
significantly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The purity of heroin from Mexico also increased significantly.
Until two years ago, Mexican cartels produced only a low grade of
heroin called "black tar," which was about seven to 20 percent
pure.
</P>
<P>
"But the purity of Mexican heroin has since climbed to an
average of 50 to 60 percent, with some seizures recorded at 76
percent purity," said the report.
</P>
<P>
U.S. authorities discovered the dramatic rise in purity levels
of Mexican heroin when 14 teenagers and young adults in one Dallas
suburb died in 1996 after using "uncut" Mexican heroin so pure
that it exploded in their systems like a bomb. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
