<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Sales Climb 5.2 Pct to New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Stimulated by a home-buying heat
in the South, the U.S. new home sales jumped 5.2 percent to a
record in April, the Commerce Department reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sales picked up to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
888,000, the most since the government began tracking them in
1963, and thus surpassed the old record of 881,000 set in
February, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
The home-buying enthusiasm is largely attributed to low
mortgage rates as well as low unemployment which hit a 28-year low
of 4.3 percent in April and steady rising income.
</P>
<P>
April marks the eighth consecutive month of sales above
800,000, the longest such period on record. The next longest
string above 800,000 for five months was recorded in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The new home sales in April were especially strong in the
South, where sales soared 18.1 percent to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 418,000, the most since December 1983.
</P>
<P>
Sales fell 9.2 percent to a rate of 157,000 in the Midwest, 3.1
percent to 95,000 in the Northeast and 0.5 percent to 218,000 in
the West.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the median price of an existing home was 147,000 in
April, down 2 percent from a year ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
