<HEADLINE> Turkey Accuses Austria of Adopting Negative Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Tuesday accused Austrian
Prime Minister Victor Klima of adopting a negative attitude toward
Ankara's efforts to win membership of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"Klima seems to be at the same point reached by the (EU)
Luxembourg summit and does not reflect the genuine realities,"
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan told a weekly
press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Klima said recently in an interview with the French newspaper
Le Figaro that Turkey would not be admitted into the EU in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey's (EU) candidateship does not seem to be acceptable."
Klima said.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided at the December summit to exclude Turkey from
its immediate expansion process, sparking harsh reaction from
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the new president of the EU will be able to come
closer to the realities and have a more realistic evaluation of
the situation," Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
Austria is to hold EU's rotating presidency on July 1 after
Britain's term expires.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been striving to enter the EU. But so far no
substantial progress has been made due to a number of differences
with the 15-nation organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
