<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Switzerland and other neutral nations kept Nazi
Germany's war machine running and were paid by Nazis with looted
gold during the World War II, said a U.S. administration report
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report concludes that although Switzerland was Nazi
Germany's banker, other neutral nations, Sweden, Portugal, Spain,
Turkey and Argentina, provided materials to keep the war going.
</P>
<P>
"The cumulative trade of the World War II European neutral
countries helped to sustain the Nazi war effort by supplying key
materials to Germany essential to their conduct of the war," said
Under Secretary of State Stuart Eizenstat at a press conference
here on the report. (US-Nazis-Gold)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Tuesday flayed the
tax service for its failure to boost tax revenue and warned of a
new crackdown on major nonpayers.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted Yeltsin as saying that tax
collection had got "not better, but worse, especially over the
past two months."
</P>
<P>
Tougher measures would be taken against the directors of major
debtor enterprises, Yeltsin said, warning that he would "dismiss
them from their posts by presidential decree and open up criminal
cases." (Russia-Yeltsin-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodian Constitutional Council was sworn in
Tuesday under the chair of Chea Sim, president of the National
Assembly, who was authorized by King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The council is an influential legal body, which will have the
power to review laws passed by the National Assembly and to
determine whether laws comply with the spirit of the
Constitution. It can also rule on election disputes and interpret
the outcome of the elections.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the Constitutional Council had been delayed by
squabbles over its political composition. Prince Norodom Ranariddh
had insisted on opposition representation on the council before he
reached a deal last month with Cambodian People's
Party. (Cambodia-Constitutional Council)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair arrived in Northern
Ireland Tuesday morning in his latest drive to bring peace to the
divided province.
</P>
<P>
Officials said Blair held talks with representatives from the
political parties involved in reaching the peace agreement to
discuss the legislative program for the assembly. This was Blair's
fourth trip to Belfast in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Belfast, Blair would also hold talks with
the Democratic Unionist Party and the United Kingdom Unionist
Party which, along with UUP dissidents, led the referendum
opposition to the pact. (UK-NIreland) 
</P>
</TEXT>
