<HEADLINE> UK Minister Says Patten to Head N.Irish Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary
Mo Mowlam on Tuesday confirmed that former Hong Kong governor
Chris Patten will head a commission to review the role of Northern
Ireland's Protestant-dominated police force.
</P>
<P>
"Can I take the opportunity this morning to confirm that the
commission will be under the chairmanship of Chris Patten," Mowlam
told the annual police federation conference in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Patten, the former chairman of the opposition party the
Conservative, had said he would accept the post if the peace deal
was approved by the May 22 referendum. A majority of voters have
endorsed the historic peace agreement in the referendum, paving
the way for the ending of the 30-year-long conflict in the divided
province.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam said she hoped to announce all the members of the
commission, whose review of the Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC)
was agreed as part of the peace accord, by Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the RUC's members are pro-British
Protestant and the police force has long been a target of
suspicion and hostility by Northern Ireland's minority Roman
Catholic community. Irish Republican Army's political wing Sinn
Fein has insisted on the reform of the RUC as part of the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam assured the 13,000-strong RUC that the pact would not
lead to the force's disbandment, as demanded by Sinn Fein.
</P>
</TEXT>
