<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Welcomes Proposed ILO Convention on Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) has hailed a new convention proposed by the International
Labor Organization (ILO), saying that it will be a milestone in
the worldwide campaign to eliminate all forms of hazardous child
labor.
</P>
<P>
"Only as we get rid of working practices which expose children
to injury, illness and death will we be on the road to abolishing
all forms of labor which deprive children of their fundamental
rights," UNICEF's Executive Director Carol Bellamy said here
Tuesday when commenting on the ILO convention under discussion.
</P>
<P>
The convention will be debated at the ILO's annual conference
here on June 2-18. Among the proposed provisions are measures for
the immediate halt to extreme and exploitative forms of child
labor and the creation of national programs to protect the very
young, especially girls.
</P>
<P>
The new convention would establish criteria for determining
work hazards and would also designate certain practices as
criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 percent of primary school children in developing
countries drop out before completion, according to UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF calls on governments to allocate 20 percent of their
budget to education and basic social services and on donors to do
the same with their official development assistance.
</P>
<P>
It estimates that it would cost six billion U.S. dollars a
year, on top of what is already spent, to put every child in
school by the year 2000. It points out that this is less than one
percent of what the world spends every year on weapons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
