<HEADLINE> Pak Sends More Relief Goods to Quake-hit Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan sent two more planeloads
of relief goods Tuesday for the quake-hit people in Badakhshan and
Takhar provinces of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A C-130 aircraft in two sorties carried 515 tents and 1,500
blankets to the calamity stricken areas on Tuesday, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Substantial quantity of foodstuff was also airlifted Tuesday,
said the sources, adding that arrangements were being made for
providing medical assistance to the Afghan areas.
</P>
<P>
On Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's directive for immediate supply
of relief goods to earthquake victims in neighboring Afghanistan,
Pakistan started airlifting relief goods since Monday.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistan Air Force aircraft on Monday airdropped 200 tents
and 1,500 blankets to victims of the earthquake measuring 7.1 on
the Richter Scale, which took place last Saturday and reportedly
killed at least 3,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that more flights are scheduled in the coming
days to help alleviate sufferings of the victims.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 sorties would be needed to transport 10,000
blankets, 1,500 tents, 10 tons of sugar and 10 tons of rice to the
affected areas, said the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
