<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Decision to Go Nuclear "Understandable": Iranian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi reaffirmed here Tuesday that "the decision by Pakistan to
go ahead with the (nuclear) tests is understandable under the
prevailing circumstances."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who left for India Tuesday afternoon, made the
remarks in a statement issued at the end of his two-day visit to
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that on the regional situation, "we received a full
briefing by Pakistan on the events which led to their decision to
conduct the tests and their present stand on the situation and
what might lie ahead."
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan, we feel, is genuinely prepared for dialogue with
India and that there are possible ideas which may be explored that
could contribute to reducing tension and containing the situation
while the larger issues are being considered," the foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"As the result, we have felt useful to go to New Delhi to
engage in discussion and further explore the possibilities for
gradually enhancing the level and means of confidence and reducing
tension with peace and security of the region in mind," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who arrived here Monday afternoon on a two-day visit
to Pakistan, is the highest-ranking foreign official to have come
to this country after its six nuclear tests on May 28 and 30.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that although the visit had been
short, he was able to have in-depth and extensive discussions on
all issues of mutual interest as well as regional matters.
</P>
<P>
On economic relations, Iran and Pakistan have agreed and
decided to pursue attentively expansion of trade in various areas.
The two countries particularly examined in detail the proposed
major oil and gas projects, according to Kharrazi.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan issue has been on the top of the agenda. Kharrazi
said that Pakistan and Iran are now in "full agreement that there
is no military solution for Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
"The two countries will, from now on, work jointly to bring the
(warring Afghan) parties to the negotiating table and to
facilitate a political settlement," he added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, the Iranian Foreign Minister called on
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and held talks with his Pakistani
counterpart Gohar Ayub Khan and Minister of State for Foreign
Affairs Siddique Kanju. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
