<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-02 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says Talks With Israeli Minister "Fruitful" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said
Tuesday he had "fruitful" talks with visiting Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai on ways to reactivate the deadlocked
Mideast peace march.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak told reporters at the end of his talks with the Israeli
official that Mordechai's Cairo visit came at his invitation.
</P>
<P>
"Our meetings have been fruitful. We met this time to see what
are the means which could help push forward the peace process," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, who arrived here before noon, has left for
home. Defense and Military Production Minister Mohamed Hussein
Tantawi, Mubarak's Political Advisor Ossama el-Baz and Israeli
Ambassador here Zvi Mazel attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which fought three wars with Israel in the past 30
years, became the first Arab nation to make peace with the Jewish
state in 1979. It has also been an important mediator in the
Arab-Israeli peace talks since 1991.
</P>
<P>
"Those who took part in war know the meaning of war and the
meaning of peace," said the president, who himself rose from the
military barracks.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel Radio reports earlier, Mordechai's talks
with Mubarak were expected to focus on the Israeli proposal to
withdraw from South Lebanon, the strategic situation in the Middle
East and means to push forward the peace process, especially on
the Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
He was believed to have explained to Egyptian officials the
Israeli stance and security requirements regarding the Israeli
second stage troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled for more
than 14 months since Israel began to build a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
Israel has rejected a latest U.S. proposal on a 13 percent
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank, whereas the Palestinian
National Authority has accepted it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
