<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intergration of African Culture in Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan minister Tuesday called
for the integration of African culture in science education when
opening the seventh Pan African Children's Book Fair here in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
At least 15 sub-Saharan African states attended the show
through the African Publishing Network. They are Kenya,
Tanzania, South Africa, Zambia, Uganda, Zimbabwe, Mauritius,
Namibia, Mali, Malawi, Senegal, Ghana, Cote d'Ivore, Botswana and
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony on Tuesday afternoon, Joseph Nyagah,
Kenyan Minister of Information and Broadcasting, urged Africa to
take steps to enhance "cross fertilization of science with
African culture in the development and provision of children's
education."
</P>
<P>
"It's essential to cultivate children's interest in science at
an early age in order to create a seed-bed for a technology
culture" in Africa on its way to industrialization, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, "while selective exposure to foreign cultural
materials in the media may broaden your knowledge, the basic
challenge is to be proud of your own heritage," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He strongly called for "serious efforts to promote our
(Africa's) own indigenous cultural productions."
</P>
<P>
"Our TV and radio program producers, film makers and others in
the entertainment and information sectors must come up with
attractive and interesting products which reflect the rich
cultural heritage of our people so as to curb dependence on
imported media programs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Africans, both adults and children, "are continually bombarded
by the out-pouring of popular culture," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Relevant education for the young people plays an important
role in the projection of national image," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he praised that the annual book fair acts as "an
international forum dedicated to focusing attention on the
information and reading needs of young people throughout the
continent."
</P>
<P>
The "book fair has undergone tremendous growth over the years"
since it was first launched in the Kenyan capital in 1992 with
"only two participating countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of kinds of colorful books for children aged between
two and 17 are on display at the fair under the theme of
"Learning Science at an Early Age."
</P>
<P>
Five school children received this year's Librarians and Avid
Readers Award at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Highlights of the fair include the launch of the
build-a-home-library campaign and the inauguration of a discount
book store and a book club.
</P>
<P>
Besides book exhibition and sales, there will also be a
children's reading tent, art and science workshop, an artists'
bazaar, children's reading competitions and a series relevant
seminars.
</P>
<P>
The six-day fair, which draws participants from nearly 40
countries both in Africa and beyond, is organized by the
Foundation for the Promotion of Children's Science Publications
in Africa formed in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
