<HEADLINE> S. Africa Rejects Nigeria's Claims of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Tuesday rejected
Nigeria's accusations that it was planning to disrupt Nigeria's
coming election, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was not interfering in Nigeria's domestic
affairs, let alone undermining its electoral process,
presidential aide Parks Mankahlana said in response to a
statement issued by Nigeria on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Abacha government said in the statement that South Africa,
the United States and Ghana were plotting to disrupt Nigeria's
presidential elections in August, and that officials from the
United States and South Africa recently met in Ghana to discuss
coordinated action.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana dismissed the claims as "just an electoral trick",
which the Abacha regime designed to mobilize voters "against as
many enemies as possible" on the eve of the polls.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana said South Africa's track record showed that it
would not cooperate with any non-African country to bring another
African government into disrepute or destabilize it.
</P>
<P>
South Africa believed its relations with Nigeria were on a
firm footing, he said.  
</P>
