<HEADLINE> Israeli Knesset Rejects No-Confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Tuesday rejected a no-confidence motion against Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu over his performance during his first two
years in office.
</P>
<P>
The motion was defeated by a vote of 41-6 with 3 abstentions,
as most of the ruling coalition parties boycotted it and didn't
took part in the vote.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, at least 61 members of the 120-seat Knesset
must vote in favor of a no-confidence motion for the prime
minister to step down. The coalition parties are currently
occupying 61 seats.
</P>
<P>
The motion was submitted by four opposition parties -- Labor,
Meretz, Hadash and National Democratic Alliance.
</P>
<P>
When summing up Netanyahu's two years in office last week,
Labor Party leader Ehud Barak accused Netanyahu of leading the
nation to war and bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Barak predicted a violent confrontation in the region that
will result in heavy casualties, caused by the stalemate in the
peace process and Netanyahu's putting his political survival
above the talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has taken a tough stance in the peace process since
he took office in June, 1996. And the Israeli-Palestinian talks
have been deadlocked for more than one year after Israel began to
build a controversial Jewish settlement in the eastern
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
