<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls for Smaller Trade Gap with Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Tuesday called for a solution to the trade
imbalance between South Africa and Malawi, saying his country's
big trade surplus with Malawi is hampering the development of
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"As long as there is that trade imbalance, the relations will
never really improve completely," Mandela said after meeting
visiting Malawian President Bakili Muluzi in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Between January and August last year, South Africa's exports
to Malawi stood at 728 million Rand (146 million U.S. Dollars),
compared with its imports from Malawi of 248 million Rand (50
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Both countries would have to explore the best approach to
achieve equity in trade, South African Press Association quoted
Mandela as saying.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi, accompanied by his ministers of foreign affairs and
commerce as well as a large business delegation, began a
three-day state visit to South Africa on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit was aimed at strengthening cooperation and
encouraging business between the private sectors of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Malawian Foreign Minister Mopopa Chipeta said he hoped that
this trip would produce a "clear plan of action" for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi met South African parliament's presiding officers and
was scheduled to tour Robben Island, where Mandela had been
jailed for 18 years, on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He would be the guest of honor at a banquet hosted by Mandela
later on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
