<HEADLINE> Egypts Renews Call for Nuclear-Free Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Tuesday called for a principled system to free the Middle East
from weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
He was telling reporters after meeting visiting Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai here.
</P>
<P>
"We call to make the area from weapons of mass destruction,"
Mubarak said, when asked to comment on Egypt's position towards
the recent nuclear tests in India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"I ask that there should be a principle to end weapons of mass
destruction all over the world and there should be an
international initiative over a number of years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has issued two initiatives in 1974 and 1991 calling for
freeing the Middle East from weapons of mass destruction in
general and nuclear weapons in particular.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed difference with Iran's reported stance that
every Muslim felt safe following the Pakistani nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"I shall feel safe if all weapons of mass destruction were
removed because this would give security to everybody in the
world," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, whose country is believed to be the only nuclear
power in the region, said Israel wants to sign the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
"We want to sign the treaty. We should not think of arms. We
should think of peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli official refused to draw comparison between the
situation in Middle East and the South Asian subcontinent where
India detonated five nuclear devices early in May, followed by
Pakistan's six nuclear blasts two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
"We live in the Middle East and not in India or Pakistan. We
look forward to realizing peace,"
</P>
<P>
Mordechai flew back to Israel Tuesday afternoon after a
few-hours visit to Cairo. Mubarak said they had "fruitful" talks
on ways to reactivate the deadlocked Mideast peace march. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
