<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Bullet Train Maker to Sell 20 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The French bullet train maker
GEC-Alsthom will begin to sell some 20 billion francs (3.3 billion
U.S. dollars) worth of stocks from later this month, announced the
group's president and chief executive officer Pierre Bilger on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The group, which also sells electricity and builds electrical
energy centers, will from now be independent and separated from
the General Electric Company (GEC) of Britain -- with which it
allied in 1989 -- and the Alcatel telecommunications group of
France.
</P>
<P>
Alsthom, now renamed Alstom, will begin to introduce from June
22 its shares in Paris, London and New York simultaneously, with
each of its shares worth from 190 to 220 francs (from 32 to 37
U.S. dollars), said Bilger.
</P>
<P>
"Alstom will be a company with fully responsible exercise for
its own destiny," said Bilger.
</P>
<P>
He said that Alstom aims to become the world's leader in two of
the three fields of its specialties -- transmission and
distribution of electricity and equipment of railways and trains.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss-Swedish ABB group is now the number one in the world
in electricity transmission and distribution business, while the
Swedish-Swiss-German Adtranz is the top producer of equipments for
railways and trains. Alstom remains the second in the two fields.
</P>
<P>
Alstom is also the number two in electrical energy business
after the General Electric of the United States, but it will not
try to surpass GE, said Bilger.
</P>
<P>
It will also abandon its Dutch legal registration and be fully
based in Paris, while its governing board imitates the model of
American companies with five non-executive chief officers.
</P>
<P>
Alstom is the joint candidate with the German Siemens for
building the Beijing-Shanghai high-speed train railway project.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the economic and financial crisis in some Asian
countries will affect the strategy of the group in the region,
Bilger said that it will not, because the countries most touched
by the crisis only have a small percentage of the investment by
the group in the region.
</P>
<P>
China and India remain the two major markets of investment for
Alstom, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
