<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Germany, France Sign Plutonium Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An intergovernmental agreement on
plutonium was signed here by Russia, Germany and France on
Tuesday, according to Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement the Russian nuclear power plants will be
able to use the plutonium obtained from dismantled nuclear
warheads and no longer needed for the country's defense.
</P>
<P>
Russian Minister for Atomic Energy Yevgeny Adamov after the
signing ceremony said, "This refers to the 50 tonnes of plutonium,
which will be processed into fuel and initially used at the
existing power plants without any substantial modification of
their reactors."
</P>
<P>
Adamov said experts from the three countries will be given two
years to draw up a feasibility study of the project. After that a
decision will be made on the construction in Russia of an
installation to turn weapons-grade plutonium into fuel for nuclear
power plants.
</P>
<P>
In Adamov's opinion, such use of weapons-grade plutonium will
decide two problems -- non-proliferation of nuclear technologies
and fuel supply to the power industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0034 </DOCNO>
