<HEADLINE> International Community Urged to Stop Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) officials Tuesday called on the international community to
take concrete steps to stop Israeli settlement activities in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to help foreign diplomats have a clearer
understanding of "gravity" of the situation in East Jerusalem,
PNA Minister of Higher Education Hanan Ashrawi and Minister for
Jerusalem Affairs Faisai Husseini led a group of foreign consuls
in Jerusalem to visit a disputed land in the Muslim quarter of
the Old City Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The land, where dozens of Jewish students from the Ateret
Cohanim religious school set up several temporary shacks last
Monday and thus triggered a violent clash between Israeli
soldiers and Palestinian legislators, was empty again after the
municipal authority ordered the students to leave and the shacks
to be torn down.
</P>
<P>
But the Antiquities Authority of Israel will begin an
exploratory excavation there under an agreement it reached with
the municipality and the Ateret Cohanim authority.
</P>
<P>
Husseini described the move as another attempt to build a
settlement in the Arab East Jerusalem, saying it would make the
negotiations between Israel and the PNA "more complicated." He
urged the Israeli side to stop such settlement actions in order
to make the permanent status talks "sooner and easier."
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi said Jerusalem is a "human heritage" and the focal
point of Israeli peace talks "not only with the Palestinians, but
also with the whole Arab world".
</P>
<P>
She urged the international community to take "concrete steps"
to put an end to "Israeli violations" of the Palestinian rights
over East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"We have to rescue Jerusalem, rescue the lands, rescue the
Palestinians and the peace itself," she said.
</P>
<P>
Before the Old City tour, Ashrawi and Husseini had a meeting
with the foreign consuls at the New Orient House, the informal
office of the PNA in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting which lasted about one hour, the PNA officials
briefed the foreign diplomats on Israeli settlement activities in
East Jerusalem, including a plan to build a 50-apartment
settlement in the center of the Old City.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Israel and the Palestinians over East
Jerusalem have flared up recently, mainly because of what the
Palestinians called intensified efforts by Israel to demolish
Arabic houses and build Jewish settlement there.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that two empty houses in East Jerusalem
were demolished Tuesday morning, but Palestinian sources put the
number at five and said all the houses belong to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
No issue is more volatile than that of the status of Jerusalem
in Israeli-Palestinian talks. Israel claims the entire city as its
"united and eternal capital" while the Palestinians want East
Jerusalem as the capital of their future state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
