<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference Calls for Addressing Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- K. Y. Amoako, Executive
Secretary of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa
(ECA), Tuesday called for policy options in addressing Africa's
underdevelopment in the field of communication technology and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the global connectivity for Africa
conference which opened here Tuesday, Amoako noted, "One aspect
of the policy option deserving attention is the fact that the
sector remains heavily dominated by state-run post and
telecommunications monopolies."
</P>
<P>
"The increasing demand for advanced communications
technologies is also putting increased pressure on the limited
infrastructure base in the sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the globalization is bringing about unique
challenges in information technology for Africa.
</P>
<P>
Forty seven African countries have Internet connectivity today
compared to a mere four in 1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, excluding South Africa, only one person in ten
thousand has access to the Internet, which is in any event
dominated by content produced in the northern countries, he said,
adding that "an overwhelming majority of Africans remain at the
very margins of the information age."
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is the first regional follow-up to
last year's Toronto Global Knowledge Conference. It is hosted by
ECA, the World Bank group, the Information for Development
Program, the International Telecommunication Union and the
African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The conference will provide a unique opportunity for
participants, including more than 30 African telecommunications
ministers, representatives of civil society as well as private
African and non-African corporations and operators, to engage in
frank dialog on the issues and options of connectivity open to
the continent and the value of information for Africa in terms of
trade and commerce.
</P>
<P>
The conference is believed to evolve concrete proposals for
cooperation in the telecommunications sector towards overcoming
Africa's development challenges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
