<HEADLINE> PNA: Arab Summit Is None of Israeli Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Tuesday brushed off an Israeli criticism of a proposed Arab
Summit, saying the summit only responds to Arab will to salvage
the Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
"Holding an Arab Summit is to free the peace process of the
deadly shackles placed by the incumbent Israeli leadership," PNA
chief delegate to the Arab League Mohamed Sobeih told Egypt's
Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"It is exclusively an internal affair of the Arabs that does
not need permission from anyone else," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih, who is also secretary of the Palestinian National
Council, dismissed statements by David Bar-Illan, senior aide to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, that seeking to hold an
Arab summit is a "flagrant violation" of the Oslo agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo agreement bans taking such measures as it stipulates
settling dispute within a direct negotiation framework and through
a mediator acceptable by both parties, the Israeli official
claimed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan was quoted by Israeli Radio as making comments on the
proposed Arab summit in Damascus or the Cairo-based Arab League
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih said Bar-Illan's statements only "inspired ridicule and
surprise on the part of Arab public and all peace-lovers
worldwide."
</P>
<P>
"An Arab summit meeting does not heed such statements. Instead,
it seeks the help of world's major powers to put an end to such
provocative statements by the Israeli leadership," he added.
</P>
<P>
Both the world public opinion and peace-loving forces in Israel
know who wants to destroy the peace process by getting it to the
current tragic situation, Sobeih said.
</P>
<P>
An Arab Summit, which has been called for by Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat, is likely to take
place in Cairo early in June to tackle the flagging peace process,
according to Arab diplomatic sources here.
</P>
<P>
But PNA Secretary General Al Tayeb Abdel Raheem said Tuesday
that the proposed Arab Summit will not be held before the United
States officially announces its peace initiative and names the
party that is responsible for blocking the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
to PNA President Yasser Arafat has promised that the U.S. will
officially announce its peace proposal soon.
</P>
<P>
Washington has reportedly proposed an Israeli troop withdrawal
from 13.1 percent of the West Bank, but Netanyahu turned it down.
</P>
<P>
Launching a drive for an Arab Summit, Arafat last week held
talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz, Moroccan King Hassan II and President Sheikh Zayed Bin
Sultan Al-Nahyan of the United Arab Emirates. He will extend the
campaign to Oman on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks collapsed 14 months ago after
Israel started to build a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
where the Palestinians want as their future capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
