<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Starts Up in Frankfurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB) made
its start-up in Frankfurt on Tuesday with its six-member board
convening their first meeting to prepare for the launch of the
single European currency euro on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
As the monetary watchdog for the euro, the ECB was inaugurated
after EU leaders last week formally appointed the bank's
president, Wim Duisenberg, along with its other five board
members: Christian Noyer of France, Eugenio Domingo Solans of
Spain, Sirkka Haemaelaeinen of Finland, Otmar Issing of Germany
and Tommaso Padoa-Schioppa of Italy.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, the ECB is due to convene its first central council
meeting, at which the six ECB board members as well as central
bank chiefs of the eleven recommended euro member states will
start to work out the common monetary policy for the whole euro
area.
</P>
<P>
A formal founding ceremony for the ECB, which is replacing its
forerunner -- the European Monetary Institute (EMI), is scheduled
for June 30 in Frankfurt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
