<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Dialog with Syria on Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian government
official said here on Tuesday that it is necessary for Jordan and
Syria to conduct direct dialog in order to iron out their
differences over the convening of an Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister for Development and Minister of Foreign
Affairs Jawad Anani made the remarks after Saudi Arabian Crown
Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz failed Monday to reconcile the
stances between Syria and Jordan over the agenda and venue of the
proposed summit aimed at reactivating the long-stalled Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Direct dialog between the two countries can help Jordan
understand the Syrian position on the summit in specific terms,
so that the kingdom can know what on earth the differences are
between them and finally iron them out, Anani told reporters at
the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"We do not specifically know what the Syrian position is
because we did not open a direct dialog with Syria," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan holds that careful preparations are needed to enhance
Arab coordination on the convocation of such a summit and the
Jordanian-Syrian dialog is just part of it, he added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has called for an Arab summit
to blame Israel for the stalemate in the Palestinian-Israeli
peace negotiations which have been deadlocked for more than a year
over the construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Syria reportedly wants the summit to be held in its capital,
Damascus, while Jordan prefers the summit to be held in the
Egyptian capital of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi crown prince arrived here Monday from Syria. His
visit to Amman aims to reconcile the views of Syria and Jordan,
which fears that an Arab summit will put brakes on its
normalization of ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and bilateral
cooperation has been conducted in the fields of trade, airport
construction and water supply. 
</P>
