<HEADLINE> Cyprus Accepts British Explanation on War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides Tuesday expressed satisfaction with explanations made
by British High Commissioner to Cyprus David Madden over a report
on war in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
But Kasoulides did not elaborate on the British explanations
when he was speaking to reporters before leaving for Italy to
attend a European Union meeting.
</P>
<P>
The London-based Sunday Times newspaper reported on Sunday that
Britain has contingency plan to airlift 250,000 people from Cyprus
over fears of a war if Cyprus goes ahead with the deployment of
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles later this year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said he is still "not satisfied with the
leak of information in this case."
</P>
<P>
He said he told Madden at a meeting Monday that the leaking of
information by the British Defense Office to the press does not
contribute to good bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Madden has said the British government has nothing to do with
the report.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said Cyprus' High Commissioner to Britain Michalis
Attalides made representations Monday to the British Foreign
Office over the report.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed the missile deal with Russia in January 1997. The
missiles are scheduled to be delivered in August. Turkey, the
United States and Britain oppose the deal. Turkey has threatened
to destroy the missiles if they are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has said its stand on the issue has not changed. But,
meanwhile, it has made it clear that it would consider not to
deploy the missiles if substantive progress is achieved in seeking
a settlement of the Cyprus problem or demilitarization of the
island is agreed by the Greek Cypriots and the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Referring to efforts to settle the protracted Cyprus problem,
the Cypriot foreign minister did not rule out the possibility of a
recourse to the United Nations Security Council if the deadlock in
the peace talks is not overcome until autumn.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot peace process came to a halt last summer when
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of the talks with
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides in protest at European Union's
decision to start accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said that he would not return to the negotiations
unless his entity in northern Cyprus controlled by the Turkish
Cypriots is recognized and the Cypriot government suspends the
talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island to protect the Turkish ethnic minorities after a failed
coup by Greek Cypriot supporters of union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
