<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Advocates Statistical Sampling in Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday advocated using statistical sampling to avoid undercounts
of minorities and the rural poor in the national census 2000.
</P>
<P>
Congressional Republicans have already voiced objection to the
method.
</P>
<P>
"It's not about politics, it's about people," news reports
quoted Clinton as saying when he visited a community center in a
heavily Latino community in Houston.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said severe undercounting of populations such as
children, minorities and homeless people is now hurting attempts
to funnel federal help to those who need it. He said the experts
agree that using statistical sampling, along with "quality checks"
that involve head counts in certain neighborhoods, can reduce the
error rate to 1/10 of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
That would mean only about 300,000 Americans may be missed in
the next census count, rather than the millions overlooked in the
1990 tally, he said.
</P>
<P>
With that tally, an estimated four million Americans nationwide
were overlooked, with higher rates of undercounting among
minorities, according to Robert Shapiro, undersecretary for
economic affairs at the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
Census results are a factor in establishing boundaries for
congressional districts. They also play a role in determining
eligibility for federal funds for an array of programs from
Medicaid to roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
Sampling is supported by congressional Democrats, who stand to
benefit if census results show higher counts in urban areas, where
voters traditionally are Democratic.
</P>
<P>
Republicans, however, object to sampling, saying the
Constitution requires that census takers literally count, not
guess, how many Americans there are.
</P>
<P>
Last year, lawmakers compromised by agreeing to conduct a test
run of the census before reaching a final decision on how to
conduct the count. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LIFFE Sets New Open Interest Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The London International Financial
Futures and Options Exchange (LIFFE) traded 15,077,480 futures and
options contracts during May 1998, according to an announcement by
the Exchange Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Average daily volume amounted to 753,874 futures and options
contracts, representing an average daily nominal turnover of 202
billion pounds (323,2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Year to date, LIFFE's cumulative volume totalled 91,052,910
futures and options contracts, up 8 per cent in the same period in
1997, LIFFE's record year.
</P>
<P>
Open interest on LIFFE soared to a new record on 15 May of
9,425,902 contracts. LIFFE has the largest open interest of any
exchange in the world which is an indication of the level of its
confidence in the market.
</P>
<P>
LIFFE is the only exchange to trade Three Month Euro futures
and a pan-European stock index future and by the fourth quarter of
this year will offer a completely innovative product, LIFFE Libor
Financed Bonds.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Hodson, LIFFE's Chief Executive said: "LIFFE continues
to strengthen its franchise in short term interest rate (STIR)
products. Year to date volume across all the STIR contracts has
grown by 57 per cent."
</P>
<P>
"We are well and truly seeking to meet the market's needs ahead
of Economic and Monetary Union (EMU)," he added.  
</P>
