<HEADLINE> Forests in E. Tanzanian Region Diminishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Coast Region runs
the risk of turning barren if the rampant felling of trees there
is left uncontrolled, Regional Commissioner Philemon
Sarungi has said.
</P>
<P>
Although the region presently has 396,000 hectares of forest,
it may look like a desert in six years if no efforts are made to
deal with people who fell trees for charcoal production, Sarungi
told a group of members of parliament who visited there over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Sarungi said that the depletion of the forests is manifested
by the decrease in charcoal production year by year.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, 761,190 sacks of charcoal were sent to
Dar es Salaam from the Coast Region in 1986 while the figures
went down to 450,000 sacks in 1988 and 161,000 sacks in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"This does not indicate that the charcoal dealers were
conscious of the problem of deforestation but reflect the
difficulty they encountered in finding suitable forests for
charcoal production," a report reaching here Tuesday quoted the
regional commissioner as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said some VIPs in the government have got involved in the
business. "We know for sure that some of the trucks ferrying
charcoal to Dar es salaam belong to influential figures. When our
guards asked them why they were involved in such business, they
just replied that they did it so as to repay the loans for their
lorries and pickups."
</P>
<P>
The regional commissioner has appealed to the members of
parliament to help the region to arrest the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
