<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- More than 70 industrial projects are awaiting
foreign investors, the Saudi English-language daily Arab News
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Consulting House has compiled a directory of the
projects ranging from food and beverages, textiles, clothes, wood
products, paper, printing and publishing, chemicals and plastic
products.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in Saudi industries stand at 26 billion
U.S. dollars while more than 340 joint ventures had been set up
till 1996.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries account for half of the foreign investments in
Saudi Arabia, followed by European and North American countries.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman has offered 12 new areas to world companies for
prospection and exploitation of oil and gas, the Arabic-language
daily Al Hayat reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Oman will sign three agreements for one of the areas this month
with three United States companies with an investment of 80
million U.S. dollars, bringing the total investments in the 12
concession areas to 400 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Agreements for the other concession areas have been signed
between Oman and Japanese, U.S., Portuguese and Saudi companies.
</P>
<P>
The Omani government has established a new mechanism for the
implementation of the agreements. It will bear no investment
expenses, while the companies will undertake all the costs.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Chairman of the Egyptian Suez Canal Authority Ahmed
Ali Fadil told the Mediterranean Naval Conference held in Cairo
on Monday that Egypt aims at deepening the international waterway
to a depth of 21.95 meters by 2010.
</P>
<P>
He said that 10,000 to 16,000 ships are sailing through the
canal every year, with an average of 40 to 50 ships every day.
</P>
<P>
He added that the cut of transit fees is taking place in
conformity with economic studies, considering the standards of
navigation, international conditions and the economic feasibility
of such a decrease.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen and the U.S. have signed three agreements on
writing off 17 million dollars of Yemeni debts to the U.S., the
Alam Al Yom newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, the payments of the remaining debts to
the U.S. commodity credit establishment and U.S. International
Development Agency have been rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
Yemen's debts to the U.S. amounted to 102 million dollars by
1995. 
</P>
