<HEADLINE> Arabs Forges United Strategy for EU-Med Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries on Tuesday forged a
united strategy politically and economically in preparation for
the coming European-Mediterranean Partnership summit.
</P>
<P>
After a two-day preparatory meeting for the summit, which was
attended by foreign ministers of nine Arab countries in the
Mediterranean basin, Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz
announced that the Arab countries had reached a consensus on all
issues which will be raised at the summit due on June 3-4 in
Palermo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to insist on a just, full and lasting peace in the
Middle East based on the principles which were formulated in the
1991 Madrid peace conference, he said at a joint news conference
with Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
They will hold Israel, especially its government, responsible
for the deadlock of the peace process due to its refusal to honor
those peace principles.
</P>
<P>
On the economic level, Boueiz said, the foreign ministers
stressed the necessity to boost cooperation with the European
Union but should not be limited to the movement of goods.
</P>
<P>
This kind of cooperation should provide facilities for the
exchange of persons and information at different levels, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said that the meeting marks a good start for
cooperation and coordination with Mediterranean and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The nine Arab countries are Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Egypt,
Tunisia, Mauritania, Algeria, Morocco and the Palestinian
National Authority.
</P>
<P>
The European-Mediterranean Partnership was launched in
Barcelona, Spain in 1995 with the aim of fostering political,
economic and cultural ties between the 15 EU member states
and 12 southern and eastern Mediterranean countries, including
the nine Arab countries, Israel and Cyprus.
</P>
</TEXT>
