<HEADLINE> Liberia Complains of ADB's Indifference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Liberia has complained about the
indifference of the African Development Bank (ADB) toword its
economic plight, a report from Abidjan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Elie Saleeby, Liberia's representative to the ADB expressed
his country's disappointment of the ADB at the regional bank's
annual meeting in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Saleeby said the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund have fielded several missions to Liberia and even
co-ordinated the donors' conference, but the ADB has only sent
one mission.
</P>
<P>
As an African institute, he said, one would have expected to
see the ADB playing a leading role in mobilizing donor support
for Liberia, both in the provision of resources and debt relief.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he said, "The bank has failed Liberia and other
post-conflict African countries."
</P>
<P>
Saleeby said the situation is particularly painful for
Liberians as the west African country had played a special role
in the conception and establishment of the ADB but failed at this
critical time, meaning that Liberia is at a difficult time as it
has just arisen from seven years of bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that huge external debt arrears have denied
Liberia the access to all traditional sources of development
assistance and served as a major impediment to the country's
reconstruction efforts after seven years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to emphasize that Liberians do not intend to
remain aid-dependent. We realize that Liberia must be rebuilt by
Liberians themselves and that ultimately we must marshal our own
human and financial resources for this purpose," he said. 
</P>
