<HEADLINE> Gingrich Pays Second Installment on Ethics Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Newt Gingrich, speaker of the
House of Representatives, has paid a second installment of 50,000
dollars toward the 300,000-dollar penalty imposed by the House
last year.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Weinstein, Gingrich's spokesman, said Tuesday that
Gingrich used his personal money to reimburse the House for the
ethics panel investigation into charges he used tax-exempt funding
to advance his political goals. He acknowledged making inaccurate
statements to the ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich made the first 50,000 dollar payment, also from
personal funds, in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Weinstein said Gingrich would use his own money to make a third
50,000 dollar payment at the end of November. In an agreement
worked out with the ethics committee, the final 150,000 dollars,
due in January 1999, can come from either personal funds or a loan
offered by 1996 Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole, the
former Senate majority leader.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich has still to decide whether he will make use of Dole's
loan offer, Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
In the year-long ethics panel probe, Gingrich denied Democratic
charges that he had misused tax-exempt donations. He reached a
plea bargain in December 1995 in which he admitted making
inaccurate statements to the committee and said he should have
used proper legal advice that would have warned him not to use
tax-exempt groups to promote political ends.
</P>
<P>
He submitted to a reprimand from the full House and agreed to
reimburse the House for the costs of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich's office maintains that the 300,000 dollars represents
just a reimbursement for the committee's investigation, and is not
a fine or a penalty. 
</P>
