<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Neutral Nations Helped Nazis in World War II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland and other neutral
nations kept Nazi Germany's war machine running and were paid by
Nazis with looted gold during World War II, said a U.S.
administration report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report concluded that although Switzerland was Nazi
Germany's banker, other neutral nations, Sweden, Portugal, Spain,
Turkey and Argentina, provided materials to keep the war going.
</P>
<P>
"The cumulative trade of the World War II European neutral
countries helped to sustain the Nazi war effort by supplying key
materials to Germany essential to their conduct of the war," said
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat at a press conference
here on the report.
</P>
<P>
The report doubled the former estimate of how much gold was in
a Nazi account in Switzerland that received deposits of wedding
rings, teeth fillings and other valuables of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, one of Germany's largest World War II trading partners,
supplied iron ore and ball bearings. Portugal and Spain provided
nearly all of Germany's tungsten used to produce weapon-grade
steel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey provided 100 percent of Germany's chromite, used to
harden steel to make armor. Argentina also did business in wartime
goods, but was most helpful as a Nazi sympathizer.
</P>
<P>
In all, those five neutral countries handled 500 million U.S.
dollars in assets for the German government and its citizens
during the war and dealt in 300 million U.S. dollars in looted
gold, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland held from 250 million to 750 million U.S. dollars
in German private and government assets, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted leaders of the Nazi-backed fascist regime
in Croatia may have used Vatican ties after World War II to escape
Europe with plundered gold from Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
The neutral nations, which also traded with the Allies and
feared a Nazi invasion if they cut off German supplies, continued
helping the Nazis until near the end of the war, said Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the motivation, whatever the pressure, it sustained
the war effort," Eizenstat said of the neutral nations' trade with
Nazi Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
