<HEADLINE> Simitis Stresses Need to Continue Efforts to Join EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
stressed Tuesday night that his government was determined to
continue its course towards taking Greece into European Economic
and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a parliamentary debate on Greece's European
prospects, Simitis said that EMU was a difficult but necessary
path, and the Greek government guaranteed the final success.
</P>
<P>
Success with EMU was inexorably linked with social cohesion and
a strengthening of the new welfare state they were daily laying
the foundations of, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed the need of making structural
changes, particularly in banks and state-run companies, to make
them more flexible and competitive.
</P>
<P>
He said Greece could develop at a rate of 8 percent a year, but
the condition was the country must readjust its productive
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Of the European Union's 15 member states, Greece is now the
only country which meets no criteria of joining EMU in January
1999. To qualify the target of joining EMU in 2001, Greece has
since this year begun a drastic economic reform including the
privatization of banks and loss-making state enterprises, but
employees of banks and public utilities have been staging strikes
to express their opposition to the government reforms. 
