<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Researchers Identify Aging Gene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A group of Canadian researchers have
identified a gene that plays a central role in aging, said reports
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They have also shown that by manipulating the gene they can
lengthen life of certain insects.
</P>
<P>
The researchers inserted a human gene called SOD1 into certain
nerve cells of fruit flies. By doing so, the life span of the
flies, which usually survive 80 days, was increased by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Then how does the SOD1 gene slow down the aging process? Dr.
John Phillips, one of the researchers, said the gene instructs
cells to produce an enzyme that counteracts the destructive
properties of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
As oxygen is used by the body, it produces waste products
called free radicals, which can damage cells. The SOD1 gene makes
sure that enough of the protective enzyme is made to neutralize or
eliminate the free radicals.
</P>
<P>
But as the body grows older, the cells become less efficient at
making the protective enzymes, said Dr. Phillips, professor of
molecular biology and genetics at the University of Guelph.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that the aging process could be slowed down by
putting more of the SOD1 gene in the motor neuron of the fruit
flies.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first step in trying to identify genes that
regulate and control aging," said one of the researchers, Dr.
Gabrielle Bouliance at the Hospital for Sick Children in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
But Bouliance and others were quick to point out that they are
far from being able to lengthen human life in a similar fashion.
</P>
<P>
Their findings were published Tuesday in the Journal Nature
Genetics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Labor Market Slackens in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singapore, June 3 (Xinhua)-- Singapore's labor market slackened
significantly in the first quarter this year as impact of the
regional economic and currency crisis sank in, a government report
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report released by the Manpower Research and Statistics
Department said that employment creation fell in the first quarter
as a result of slowdown in the economic activities. The total
employment increase was 9,064 jobs, lower than the gain of 16,159
in the same quarter last year and much lower than the traditional
high increase of 35,805 in the last quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Retrenchment reached a record quarterly high. A total of 7,131
workers were retrenched in the first quarter, which was the
highest quarterly figure recorded since the data was first
compiled in 1983 and constituted 73 percent of the retrenchment in
the whole of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary estimate of the number of unemployed persons in
March 1998 was 43,500, notably higher than 37,200 in December and
35,100 in September 1997. The seasonally adjusted overall
unemployment rate in March 1998 rose to 2.2 percent from 2.0
percent in last December and 1.8 percent in September 1997.
Notwithstanding, the jobless rate remained significantly lower
than the average of 5.7 percent reached in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The number of job vacancies dropped to an all-time low of
26,148, representing a 44 percent reduction compared to a year
ago. The vacancy rate fell from 5 percent to 2.7 percent, the
lowest ever recorded since the quarterly data was compiled in
1987.
</P>
<P>
Labor turnover continued to fall with the resignation rate
declining to 2.5 percent from 3.2 percent in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The weakening in demand for labor was also reflected in less
overtime hours. The weekly overtime hours averaged 4.2 hours in
the first quarter of 1998, lower compared with 4.6 hours a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
The report said that unless the economic situation improves,
labor demand in Singapore is likely to soften and employment is
expected to rise as graduates will be entering the labor market in
the next few months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
