<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt, German and Italy clinched a contract Tuesday to
jointly exploit the Aswan iron ore in southern Egypt, with a total
investment of 1.5 billion Egyptian pounds (443 million dollars),
the Al Hayat newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Egyptian Industry and Mineral
Minister Suleiman Reda said the iron ore will be exempt from
taxation for 20 years as of the date of production.
</P>
<P>
The annual output of the iron ore is estimated at 3 million
tonnes, the amount just to fill the gap between Egypt's needs of 7
million tonnes and its production capacity of 4 million tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the companies from the three countries will
also jointly produce steel bars, seamless steel pipes, railway
tracks and other steel products used as building materials.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A fertilizer plant in Abu Dhabi, the biggest in
the Middle East, started operation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It will produce 200,000 tonnes of fertilizer annually, including
80,000 tonnes of compound fertilizer and 40,000 tonnes of liquid
fertilizer, an official of the factory said.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate reached 8.4 percent in
the first quarter of the year, the highest since the last quarter
of 1993, triggering new debate over the government's economic
policy.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics available Wednesday, the unemployment
rate is 1 percent higher than that in the same period of last year
and 0.8 percent higher than that of the previous quarter. It means
some 189,000 people are without work.
</P>
<P>
The figures aroused a storm among politicians and labor
experts, partly because Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman has
recently said that the country's economy has begun to turn around.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Despite a sharp fall in oil earnings of the oil
giant, Iran managed to reduce its foreign debts to 12.56 billion
U.S. dollars by the end of 1997 from 16.8 billion dollars in March
1996.
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the Central Bank of Iran (CBI) available
Wednesday showed that Iran's long- and medium-term foreign debts
stood at 9.68 billion dollars while its short-term debts were 2.88
billion dollars by end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, if contingent obligations, including opened letters of
credit not yet consigned and future interest, were taken into
account, Iran's total external debts would reach 24.5 billion
dollars, the CBI report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
