<HEADLINE> India Continues to Flight-Test Surface-to-Air Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- India's naval version of
surface-to-air missile "Trishul" was flight tested from an Indian
naval ship in Cochin port of southwestern India Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The missile was last test-fired in Orissa State of eastern
India on May 11 when India also conducted three underground
nuclear tests at Pokharan of Rajasthan State.
</P>
<P>
This is the first development flight test of the missile in a
series before it is offered for user trials and this time it used
new and advanced guidance technologies, a Defense Ministry
spokesman said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The naval version of the missile is designed for two roles with
the India navy -- as a surface-to-air missile against adversary
aircraft and, as a counter to sea-skimming missiles launched
against Indian warships, he said.
</P>
<P>
Trishul missile is part of the integrated guided missile
program which includes intermediate range ballistic missile
"Agni", surface-to-surface missile "Prithvi", surface-to-air
missile "Akash" and anti-tank missile "Nag", he further said.
</P>
<P>
User trial of this version of Trishul is expected to be
completed this year, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
