<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scowcroft Urges Stronger Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A stronger and more
comprehensive Sino-American relationship would heighten regional
security and support trade and investment, says former United
States National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States last
year established a new premise for Sino-American relations and the
two presidents demonstrated a shared commitment to cooperation and
what was characterized as a "strategic partnership," Scowcroft
said in response to written questions by Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation would come in three modes: coordinated action,
where useful, on issues of common interests; issues where there
are sharp differences would be set aside, but would not prevent
cooperation elsewhere; on open issues of those where differences
are not basic, solutions and common grounds would be sought,
according to Scowcroft.
</P>
<P>
"In plain words, this means that the foundation for discussion
of any issue -- be it economic or security -- will be a common
interest and a desire to avoid conflict," said Scowcroft, who
served as Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs
for former Presidents Gerald Ford and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
Through President Bill Clinton's reciprocal visit, which
Scowcroft called "really the second half of the summit," he shows
the American people that relations require direct exchanges at the
highest level, Scowcroft said.
</P>
<P>
"This summit confirms that the friendship between the two
countries is founded in basic interests, and is strong and
genuine," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said two events had occurred since President Jiang's visit
that gave weight to the idea that the U.S. and China had many
interests in common.
</P>
<P>
First, the deepening crisis in Asia reveals how important the
region is to the health and prosperity of both the Chinese and
American economies, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has received a great deal of credit in the eyes of
American policy makers for its support for stability in the region
-- both through direct assistance and by its commitment to a
strong and stable Renminbi, the Chinese currency.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has exercised its leadership as well. We
both need Asian economies that are healthy and stable," Scowcroft
said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, he said the decision by India to test several nuclear
devices reminds everyone that South Asia remains one of the most
dangerous places in the world.
</P>
<P>
China had achieved an understanding with India that seemed to
provide an end to their troublesome border dispute, only to have
the Indian defense minister warn of an imagined Chinese threat to
India, resurrecting old fears in both countries, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Education Chief Appeals for Whole-day Primary Schooling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Director of Education Helen Yu of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) appealed
Wednesday to principals and teachers to work together for an
earlier implementation of whole-day primary schooling.
</P>
<P>
Yu said her department will endeavor to secure more resources
to enhance the quality of education including improving the
class/teacher ratio in primary schools. "We firmly believe that
whole-day primary schooling provides a better environment for
students to learn, to interact with peers and teachers and to take
part in extra-curricular activities," she said.
</P>
<P>
The education chief said she noticed that this view had been
supported by educational bodies, which had been urging the
government to speed up the implementation of such a schooling
system.
</P>
<P>
The Education Department is raising the percentage of students
in whole-day primary schools from the previous target of 40
percent to 60 percent by the 2002-2003 school year, with the
ultimate goal of whole-day schooling for all.
</P>
<P>
SAR's Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa had undertaken to announce
the time-table for achieving this target in his next Policy
Address, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
"Our major difficulty now is finding sufficient sites for new
schools," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the target, the department had considered taking
various measure including building more new primary schools by
2002-2003, designing smaller schools to optimize land use, using
all vacant classrooms where applicable and building additional
classrooms where feasible.
</P>
<P>
And the average class size was to be decreased, which, as Yu
put it, "is a price worth paying for the benefits that whole-day
schooling brings to the learning environment of our children."
</P>
<P>
The time-table was being actively drawn up for full
implementation of whole-day primary schooling. "The success of
quality education depends much on the leadership and dedication of
 our teaching profession," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scowcroft Urges Stronger Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It is imperative that the United States and China continue and
enhance our shared efforts at nonproliferation and building
regional security," he said. This should include discussion of a
coordinated approach to Pakistan's security.
</P>
<P>
Triggered by India's explosion of its nuclear devices, Pakistan
had recently detonated six underground nuclear devices. Both China
and the United States had tried to dissuade Pakistan from staging
the tests and expressed regret over the development which, it is
feared, could further endanger the security in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Calling for enhanced mutual understanding, Scowcroft said,
"There is a serious lack of understanding in both countries about
the fundamentals of the relationship, and too much uninformed
rhetoric."
</P>
<P>
More than 25 years after the signing of the Shanghai
Communique, he said, "I doubt that half the members of the
U.S. Congress can explain the document. So too, there have been a
host of books published in China which demonize the United States."
</P>
<P>
"Our fortunes are linked, and we owe it to our populations to
provide accurate portrayals of the other country and its people,"
Scowcroft said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm confident that, when we talk honestly about our interests
and intentions, the public in both countries will find that
picture persuasive. We demonstrate shared interests by our actions
and by how we deal with one another everyday."
</P>
<P>
Asked about the impact of Sino-American relations, Scowcroft
said, "A stronger, more comprehensive Sino-American relationship
-- where consultation between policy makers and military leaders
at all levels is the norm -- would heighten regional security and
support trade and investment." He said that more consistent and
improved cooperation between the two countries is a threat to no
one and can pay dividends throughout the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
"We need not always agree -- our relationships are complex and
becoming more so. But our economies are converging, and we have
tens of thousands of student exchanges every year, countless
business people, and more government and military officials than
ever before," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our interests are overwhelmingly congruent, and our
capabilities are often complementary. Neither government can
afford a failed bilateral relationship, and there is no excuse for
failure now."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leadership is justifiably confident about the
future of China, and the United States is enjoying record
prosperity, he said.
</P>
<P>
The best relations between countries are possible when both
governments are popular and secure.
</P>
<P>
"We do not need grand announcements or dramatic new agreements
to sustain the relationship now, and none should be expected," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The upcoming summit should affirm mutual respect, and
highlights China's progress and the improved life of the ordinary
Chinese people," Scowcroft said.
</P>
<P>
"Visible examples of cooperation between the two in dealing
with issues of world significance, such as the Asian financial
crisis or stability in the Gulf, would have a profound, favorable
impact both regionally and globally," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
