<HEADLINE> Kurdish Rebels Kill 9 Civilians in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) shot dead nine Turkish civilians in the
southeast of the country on Wednesday, the Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
A group of PKK militants stopped a minibus near Sagman village
in Pertek town of Tunceli province at 11:45 local time (0845 GMT)
and ordered the passengers to get off.
</P>
<P>
The rebels fired with automatic weapons at the passengers after
they disembarked, killing nine and wounding two others, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the PKK guerrillas escaped after the killing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Turkish security forces killed six PKK rebels in
a military operation in the towns of Eruh and Pervari of the
southeastern province of Siirt.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish
state in the southeast of Turkey. More than 35,000 people,
including PKK militants, government troops and civilians, have
been killed in the war between the government and PKK rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
