<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West African Gas Pipeline Project Soon to Take </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the long-awaited
West African Gas Pipeline project will finally take off this
year, an official of the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) confirmed to Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian media have quoted John Sese, director of the ECOWAS
Department of Traffic and Energy as saying in Lagos Monday that
the survey for the project will be completed in October and that
construction will start immediately.
</P>
<P>
Contacted on the phone from her office in the ECOWAS
secretariat in Abuja, the sub-regional body's spokesperson
Adriemne Diop confirmed that "everything Sese said is correct."
</P>
<P>
The West African Gas Pipeline project was signed in Abuja in
September 1995. The first phase of the project is expected to be
completed by 1999, when the rich natural gas of Nigeria will be
piped to Togo, Ghana and the Republic of Benin.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the pipeline is expected to be expanded to the
whole west African sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Lagos, Sese pointed out that the energy crisis in
several west African countries have caused serious concern for
ECOWAS, which may explain why the project is gathering momentum
after years of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
Sese disclosed that the ECOWAS is trying to get private
enterprises interested in the project, the cost of which is put
at about 260 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
