<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola to Open Trade to S. African Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Trade Minister Vitorino Hossi said
here Wednesday Angola will open its trade to southern African
countries starting July to boost business and promote mutual
development.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement to the press at the Luanda
International Airport after returning from a World Trade
Organization (WTO) meeting in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Hossi revealed that the Angolan government will sign trade and
industry agreements with southern African states in July in a bid
to open its trade to them.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister noted that open trade might also bring
about a series of problems. Therefore, it is necessary to make
appropriate adjustment to the country's administrative and
financial institutions to meet future challenges.
</P>
<P>
Agreements with countries in the region on trade and industry
will also lead to certain revision on tariff, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the WTO Geneva meeting, Hossi said the meeting
will exert positive impact on international trade and explore new
prospects for trade, especially electronic trade.
</P>
<P>
Currently Angola has close trade relations with the United
States and European countries which export most of the products
Angola needs. Trade with other neighboring countries is however,
quite scarce.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that Angola's decision to open its trade to
southern African states will boost its trade with other countries
in the region and promote its trade and economic ties with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
