<HEADLINE> Roundtable Workshop Organized in HK on Innovation, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's Commission
on Innovation and Technology of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) on Wednesday organized a workshop to
arouse public awareness and debate about such issues as the
current and future challenges facing SAR's economy.
</P>
<P>
The 40 members of the workshop -- all prominent figures from
the business, academic and public sectors -- exchanged views on
what a center of innovation and technology should mean for Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
A Commission spokesman later introduced areas discussed by the
participants, which also included whether Hong Kong SAR should
aspire to become the Silicon Valley of East Asia or to follow the
experiences of other economies in Asia; the choice between "high
tech" and high value-added activities and between manufacturing
and service industries; and the synergistic relationship between
the Hong Kong SAR and the adjacent Pearl River Delta.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Commission would organize
additional workshops in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Commission was appointed by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
in March 1998 to advise him on the measures necessary to make Hong
Kong a center of innovation in East Asia. It is due to submit a
first report to Tung by October this year, and will complete all
its tasks within 12 to 18 months. 
</P>
