<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historical Letter of Invitation Made Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A letter written 49 years ago by
a member of the Communist Party of China (CPC) inviting a top
scientist to return to the motherland was made public here today.
</P>
<P>
The scientist was Qian Xuesen, who has made significant
contributions to China's success in guided missile and space
technology research.
</P>
<P>
On May 14, 1949, commissioned by the CPC's Central Committee,
Cao Richang, a professor of psychology in Hong Kang and a member
of the CPC, wrote a letter to Qian, then in the US, which reads as
follows:
</P>
<P>
"The whole country will soon be liberated. The north and
northeast parts of China are already at peace, and all kinds of
industries are now under re-construction, including the aviation
industry.
</P>
<P>
"The authority in the north [the CPC] has been looking forward
to meeting you for a long time, but due to bad communication
conditions they can not greet you directly, so I was entrusted to
write to you.
</P>
<P>
"We hope you can return to the motherland as soon as possible,
to play a leading role in laying a foundation for the aviation
industry in the north."
</P>
<P>
Not knowing Qian's address, the letter was mailed to Ge
Tingsui, one of the sponsors of the Association of Chinese
Scientists in America, for him to pass on.
</P>
<P>
Ge transcribed the letter in a notebook which is still
preserved.
</P>
<P>
On May 20, 1949, about four months before the founding of
the People's Republic of China, Ge mailed the letter to Qian and
wrote another letter to him, which says:
</P>
<P>
"As far as I know, the authority in north China is very
enthusiastic about the improvement of technology. Under the
pre-condition of serving the public, absolute freedom is ensured.
</P>
<P>
"If you, well-known in the international academic community,
can return to the motherland immediately, many more Chinese
scholars currently staying overseas will follow you, which will
greatly benefit New China."
</P>
<P>
Also made public today was a letter from former senior Chinese
leader Hu Yaobang to mathematician Hua Luogeng, and a
clock presented as a gift to Chinese scientist Tan Jiazhen by
Chiang Wei-kuo, son of Chiang Kai-shek.
</P>
<P>
All these letters and related objects are among a number of
relics donated by members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and
the Chinese Academy of Engineering to the Museum of the Chinese
Revolution here today.
</P>
<P>
In June 1992, when Tan visited Taiwan, he met with his
student Chiang Wei-kuo and received a clock from Chiang, on which
Chiang wrote:
</P>
<P>
"People on both sides of the Taiwan Strait all identify
themselves as Chinese, so we need only one China; We hope every
Chinese can have the opportunity to lead a good life. China should
gain respect from the whole world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0086 </DOCNO>
