<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Not to Discuss Bill on Cooperation With Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, on Wednesday rejected a proposal that a bill
on Russia's cooperation with Taiwan be put on its agenda, the
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
The bill was prepared by Duma's Geopolitics Committee while the
proposal to discuss it was drafted by Chairman of Liberal
Democratic Party of Russia (LDPR) Vladimir Zhirinovsky.
</P>
<P>
Duma Speaker Gennady Seleznyov said that the State Duma opposed
the bill because Duma "does not know the existence of such a
country (named Taiwan)." Taiwan is a province of China.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Duma's Committee on International Affairs
Vladimir Lukin said the LDPR faction in effect proposed that
Taiwan, part of China, be recognized as a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
Lukin also cautioned his colleagues not to support the motion,
saying "this draft law contradicts our constitution and all
international obligations of Russia."
</P>
<P>
Only 77 Duma deputies voted for Zhirinovsky initiative when it
needed 226 votes to be passed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
