<HEADLINE> Japan Plans International Forum on N-Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan plans to open an international
forum of experts to discuss recent nuclear tests by India and
Pakistan, and seek ways to maintain the nuclear non-proliferation
regime.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi is expected to propose
the international forum at a June 12 meeting in London of foreign
ministers from the Group of Eight (G-8) industrialized countries,
Chief Cabinet Secretary Kanezo Muraoka said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to have experts at home and abroad compile a
proposal for governments concerned as early as possible on
concrete ways to maintain and strengthen the nuclear
nonproliferation regime and speed up world nuclear disarmament,"
the Japanese spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The forum may mainly consist of experts from non-government
sectors, but government experts, as private persons, would be
allowed to join the gathering, Japanese Foreign Ministry officials
said.
</P>
<P>
India detonated five nuclear devices on May 11 and 13,
triggering off a nuclear arms race in South Asia. India's nuclear
tests prompted Pakistan to respond with its own nuclear tests on
May 28 and 30.
</P>
<P>
Forty-six countries attending an extraordinary meeting in
Geneva of the Conference on Disarmament condemned India and
Pakistan on Tuesday and urged them to join the Comprehensive Test
Ban and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation treaties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
