<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Conference Calls for Improved Grain Circulation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji stressed
today that all surplus grain must be purchased at protective
prices, state-owned grain enterprises must sell grain at slightly
profitable prices to avoid losses and grain purchasing funds must
be used properly.
</P>
<P>
At a national TV-telephone conference on grain purchasing and
marketing, Zhu asked grain enterprises to step up their efforts at
reforming themselves to improve grain circulation.
</P>
<P>
The conference urged local grain purchasing and storage
enterprises to buy all surplus grain from farmers at protective
prices so as to protect farmers' interests and mobilize their
initiative for farming.
</P>
<P>
Grain enterprises must purchase grain from farmers all year
round. They may buy low-quality grain at lower prices but
cannot refuse to purchase it.
</P>
<P>
Except for agricultural taxes, grain enterprises are not
allowed to set aside other items of fees or taxes at the request
of township or village officials, who in turn are not allowed to
charge various improper fees at grain purchasing sites.
</P>
<P>
According to the conference, farmers' grain can only be bought
by state-owned grain enterprises. Non-state-owned businesses or
individuals are banned from direct purchase of grain from farmers.
</P>
<P>
The conference noted that state grain enterprises must sell
grain at prices which include purchasing prices, reasonable
expenses and minimum profits. Only in this way can the enterprises
prevent new losses and make up accumulated losses.
</P>
<P>
In terms of retail of grain, state-owned grain enterprises can
decide their own selling prices on the basis of certain profits,
and local governments or pricing departments are not allowed to
fix unified floor prices.
</P>
<P>
State grain enterprises must not sell grain while losing money
in business. Governments at all levels have the responsibility
for supervising grain enterprises to purchase and sell grain on
a profitable basis, according to the conference.
</P>
<P>
In addition, grain purchasing funds from the Agricultural
Development Bank must be used for grain enterprises to purchase
grain; they must not be used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
As soon as grain enterprises sell their grain, they must return
the principal and interest to the bank promptly. In the meantime,
financial departments of local governments should not order
state-owned grain enterprises to hand over their profits to higher
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The conference also pointed out that the fundamental way out
for state grain enterprises lies in reform. Only in this way can
they increase their competitiveness on the market and be
responsible for their own profits and losses.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the enterprises should downsize
staff, enhance efficiency, expand service fields and improve
internal management, according to the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Waterhouse Praises China's New Assets Assessment System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The leading international
accounting firm Price Waterhouse today said China's adoption of a
new assets classification system will help the Chinese banking system
improve its transparency and comparability with the international
banking community.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the central bank, has decided to
introduce a new five-degree loan risks classification system in
August to its state-owned commercial banks in a move to improve
credit loan management.
</P>
<P>
J. Thomas Macy, chairman of Price Waterhouse's Financial
Service Practice China, said that this internationally-recognized
system will present many exciting opportunities for Chinese banks
to strategically position themselves in this highly competitive
market.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the system, which was first implemented in
the United States, has been widely adopted by banks in developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
He called it an "early warning" system, a system that "looks
forward." He noted that it focuses on identifying problems at an
early stage so as to ensure a timely solution to the problems.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Macy said that since in the
past Chinese banks practised a different assets classification
system, it was difficult for the international banking community
to know the real situation of the Chinese banks.
</P>
<P>
"The adopting of the new rules will help the foreign financial
institutions to get to know better the performance of the Chinese
banks and boost the confidence of foreign investors," he observed.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Yong, a partner in Price Waterhouse, told Xinhua that
his company began to cooperate with China's central bank in 1995
to introduce on a trial basis the new system to several commercial
bank branches in China.
</P>
<P>
Today Price Waterhouse held a seminar here featuring the
implementation of the assets classification system. High-ranking
executives and credit officers from a dozen Chinese banks attended
the event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
