<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's GDP Roses 1.3 Percent in March Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Australia's gross domestic product
(GDP) rose by 1.3 percent in the March quarter that would lead the
annual growth rate to 4.9 percent, the highest since 1994.
</P>
<P>
While commenting on the latest statistics issued by the
Australian Bureau of Statistics Wednesday, federal Treasurer Peter
Costello said Australia now has become one of the world's
fastest-growing economies after its annual economic growth surged
to a three-year high in the first three months of 1998 despite the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Costello capitalized on the figures, saying "this means that
Australia is probably the fastest growing country in the
industrialized world and certainly a strong economy of the Asian
region."
</P>
<P>
But behind the headline 4.9 percent annual GDP growth, the
national accounts data also offered worrying signs that the Asian
turmoil was beginning to bite.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending fell for the first time in five years, while
stocks showed a rapid build-up.
</P>
<P>
Costello warned that the growth would slow to the lower 3
percent range in 1998/99, while remaining solid by world
standards.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Perth Radio, Prime Minister John Howard
regarded the data as proof that the government had safeguarded the
economy against the Asian turmoil. He said the figures showed most
economic indicators were running as strongly as they could.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, the economy is really performing well, we have given
it security and safety amidst all of this Asian economic turmoil."
</P>
<P>
Opposition treasury spokesman Gareth Evans said the headline
figures were welcome, but warned they were "a mirage" based on a
rapid build-up of stocks, and hid flat business investment and
private consumption.
</P>
<P>
"Today's growth figures are one-off, unsustainable and give no
hope at all to Australia's jobless," he told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
