<P>
MONROVIA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sepp Blatter, currently FIFA's
secretary general, promised on Tuesday in Monrovia's soccer
stadium the 2006 World Cup to Africa if he is elected president of
soccer's world ruling body FIFA next week.
</P>
<P>
"I will not give you all my programmes for Africa, but what I
can promise, which will be a reality, is that if I am elected
president of FIFA, I will give the 2006 World Cup to Africa," said
the presidency candidate in a campaign speech.
</P>
<P>
Blatter contends with European Football Union (UEFA) chief
Lennart Johansson in a bid to succeed Joao Havelange as president,
to be resolved at the FIFA congress in Paris next Monday.
</P>
<P>
His pledge was responded by promises of support for his
election from Liberian officials.
</P>
<P>
"If you receive one vote, that ballot will be the one from
Liberia," said Edwin Snowe, the president of Liberian Football
Association.
</P>
<P>
Blatter promised Liberia additional FIFA cash in return to
rehabilitate the country's soccer facilities destroyed during
nearly eight years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
"Liberia will receive more money than the others because of
your delicate situation", said Blatter.
</P>
<P>
The official said several African countries had promised him
their votes, among them Guinea, Sierra Leone and Mauritania, whose
soccer chief was in his delegation during the one-day visit to
Liberia. 
