<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Warn of Water Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China will probably face a water
crisis by the mid-21st century if no measures are taken to curb the
worsening water shortage.
</P>
<P>
This warning appears in a report titled "Water Shortage and
Possible Solutions", drawn up by over 30 scientists and experts
from the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), the Chinese Academy of
Engineering (CAE), the Ministry of Water Resources and the Ministry of
Education.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, which was released here today, about
half of over 600 cities across the country are suffering from
water shortages, which lead to an annual loss of 200 billion yuan
(about 25 billion US dollars) in industrial production and cuts
grain output by 15 billion kg to 20 billion kg.
</P>
<P>
China's total industrial output was valued at 5,371 billion
yuan and its grain output amounted to 490 billion kg in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The report says thats demand for water will go up to 800
billion cu m by the mid-21st century from the present 500 billion
cu m, accounting for 28 percent of its usable water reserves.
</P>
<P>
"International experiences tell us that a water crisis will
arise when the demand exceeds 20 percent of the total reserves,"
the report points out.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zonghu, a prominent scientist at CAS, listed serious
waste and pollution as major causes of the water shortage in
China, in addition to other reasons like reduced rainfall.
</P>
<P>
In the agricultural sector which accounts for half of the total
water consumption, the actual waste is as high as 60 percent, said
Zhang. "China can save 100 billion cu m to 120 billion cu m of
water each year if farming irrigation improves the efficiency of
the use of water by 0,2 percent."
</P>
<P>
Currently, one third of industrial waste water or 90 percent of
waste water from people's daily lives are discharged into rivers
and lakes without being treated. As a result, ninety percent of
cities have reported deteriorating water quality.
</P>
<P>
The report points out the only solution is to implement water
conservation in every social sector and gradually cut water
consumption.
</P>
<P>
CAS academician Xu Guanhua said that a group of CAS experts
will begin an investigation tour along the Yellow River to find
out the cause of frequent flow stoppages of the country'
second-longest river.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Washington-based World Watch issued a warning
report on the fact that dry-ups in parts of the Yellow River
totaled 226 days in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
