<HEADLINE> Corretja Reaches French Semifinals as Third Spaniard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Alex Corretja became the third
Spaniard to move into the men's seminfinals as he clinically
disposed of Belgian Filip Dewulf 7-5, 6-4, 6-3 at the French Open
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 14th seed's victory over Dewulf, the 1997 semifinalist,
underscored Spanish men's dominance on slow clay courts after
Felix Mantilla and Carlos Moya made to the last four on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old baseliner will play his first grand slam
semi-final against the winner of the last quarter-final later on
Wednesday between France's Cedric Pioline and Morocco's Hicham
Arazi.
</P>
<P>
Dewulf, 26, got off to the better start as he broke Corretja
early and moved into a 5-3 lead in the opening set, having lost
just four points in four service games.
</P>
<P>
But Corretja broke Dewulf for 5-5 with his heavy and topspin
groundstrokes and two games later a whipped cross-court backhand
passing shot gave the first set to the Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
Corretja never allowed his 39th-ranked opponent back into the
match and errors began to creep into Dewulf's game before his
devastating forehand deserted him and a wide and long groundstroke
off that side gave victory to Corretja after one hour 50 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
