<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers's Players Hope Coach Bird to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indiana Pacers coach Larry
Bird, who said he wanted to quit the position after the team
exited the playoffs, was voted as a brilliant coach by the Pacers
in a poll.
</P>
<P>
Guard Mark Jackson dismissed Bird's idea as "stupid". Chris
Mullin, who played with Bird on "Dream Team I", said the coach's
success speaks for itself. Reggie Miller said Bird delivered
everything he promised.
</P>
<P>
Before the voting, Bird said: "My golf game is a little
rusty. I can always pick that back up."
</P>
<P>
But nobody said he should leave the team. Pacers president
Donnie Walsh said the question was moot until Larry asked him
personally.
</P>
<P>
"What Indiana accomplished and what Larry Bird accomplished in
his first year benefits all of us in the NBA for years to come,"
said NBC Sports president Dick Ebersol.
</P>
<P>
Bird took the job with the team coming off its worst season in
a decade, wrapping up a record of 39 wins and 43 losses. Bird, who
was named the NBA Coach of the Year, guided the Pacers to 58
victories - the second longest runners-up record in Eastern
Conference - in the regular season this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 27 Hall of Fame players who preceded Bird into the
coaching ranks, only Lenny Wilkens will get back to the hall as a
coach.
</P>
<P>
As a new coach at any level, Bird worked out his own way to
lead the team. The veterans got almost complete freedom.
</P>
<P>
He recognized Jackson could run a ballclub, so he handed him
the keys. He knew Miller, Mullin and Rik Smits could be trusted to
take good shots, so he gave them permits. Bird also gave younger
guys like Jalen Rose freedom to let them flourish in turn.
</P>
<P>
"He hasn't said one time since he's been here who he is or
what he's done," Antonio Davis said."But everybody knows."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
