<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Judge on Civil Courts' Role in Intellectual Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The civil courts are the natural
forum for the enforcement of intellectual property rights, Justice
Rogers J.A. of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Considering the relative functions of the civil and criminal
law in the field of intellectual property rights, the most
appropriate courts to enforce intellectual property rights are
courts exercising civil jurisdiction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Justice Roger was speaking at the three-day World Intellectual
Property Organization (WIPO) Asian Regional Symposium, which
closed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Intellectual property rights are private rights -- it is up to
the individual holders of those rights to identify, claim and
protect their interests. They can do that by bringing an action in
the civil court," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rogers said civil courts award damages to compensate the
injured party as well as injunctions to stop
infringement. "Damages awarded in the recent past have come to
very high figures," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the enforcement of intellectual property rights by
criminal prosecutions, Rogers said that the criminal law was an
appropriate tool where there had been trademark counterfeiting or
copyright piracy as opposed to mere infringement. In criminal
cases, the prosecution is brought by the government at public
expense.
</P>
<P>
"The power of criminal sanction is needed, but it must be
exercised with discretion and good judgment," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The WIPO Symposium was designed to create a forum for the
discussion of the Agreement on the Trade Related aspects of
Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS), one of the subsidiary
agreements of the Agreement Establishing the World Trade
Organization (WTO) and binds all 132 WTO members. TRIPS also
expands the scope and protection of the intellectual property
rights to trade related issues.
</P>
<P>
Roger praised the symposium as "useful." "In the first place
by bringing together those involved in the implementation of the
TRIPS Agreement, it has provided a broader perspective of how
TRIPS works around the world.
</P>
<P>
"In the second place it has enabled a number of important
points about TRIPS to be discussed. It must always be remembered
that intellectual property rights constitute monopolies and
monopolies should only exist if they can be shown to be in the
public interest," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
