<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transgenically-Produced Drugs Being Researched in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Drugs produced with transgenic
technology may dominate China's huge pharmaceuticals market in
future. But they are still being researched, according to a Chinese
geneticist involved in the field.
</P>
<P>
"The milk of transgenic animals contains a human gene which
provides therapeutic protein. Medicines produced from the milk may
become powerful weapons against difficult illnesses, like cancers
and hereditary diseases," said Prof. Zeng Yitao, an academician of
the Chinese Academy of Engineering.
</P>
<P>
Research results have suggested that not only hereditary
diseases, but cancers and cardiovascular diseases, are associated
with defects in certain genes. A transnational program to map
all human genes, known as the Human Genome Project (HGP), is being
conducted in order to identify which genes can cause illnesses.
</P>
<P>
"Once they discover a pathogenetic gene, scientists will know
what kind of gene to inject into mammals, such as sheep, cows
or pigs, to enable them to produce milk which contains a certain
therapeutic protein," Prof. Zeng said in an interview with Xinhua
today.
</P>
<P>
Despite the possible debut of such medicines on the world market
this year, China may develop such products in another three to
five years, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Medical Research Institute of Genetics, where Zeng
works, has co-operated with Fudan University to breed five
transgenic goats. One goat has produced milk carrying the IX
Factor, or plasma thromboplastin component (PTC), which can be
used to treat hemophilia.
</P>
<P>
Commercial production of transgenically-produced drugs with low
production costs will be the most profitable industry in the future,
Zeng predicted, adding that the annual sales may hit 25 billion US
dollars in ten years time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, transgenic technology has been adopted to breed
better grain varieties which can resist drought, frost or
pests, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The professor is in Beijing to attend an ongoing biennial
conference of academicians of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and
the Chinese Academy of Engineering.
</P>
<P>
Transgenic goat research has been supported by the country's
"863" High-Tech Plan since 1990.
</P>
<P>
China has established two research centers of transgenic
animals in the Shanghai Institute and the Beijing-based China
Agriculture University, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Warn of Thailand's Debt Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand would not see a true
economic recovery unless its debt problem was resolved, economic
experts warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending a seminar here on the resolution of
Thailand's debts said that alleviation of the debt problem
remained a key obstacle to the economy's recovery.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government should help lower the private sector's
debts to stop the economy from collapsing even further, they said,
suggesting that this be done without the use of public money and
the state act as a facilitator in the process of bringing the
creditors and debtors together.
</P>
<P>
This strategy, the experts said, would encourage foreign banks
to roll over short-term debts and reach individual settlements
with debtors. Thailand's debts now stand at 90 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, the roll-over rate of 85 percent is
actually dropping. With an estimated 4 billion U.S. dollars due
each month, a 15 percent maturity rate puts tremendous pressure on
the balance of payments.
</P>
<P>
The maturity structure for roll-overs is very short, only
extended from one to three months, because head offices are keen
to keep their options open. Moreover, Japanese banks, by far the
largest single creditor group, are facing a difficult situation at
home with widening premiums reducing roll-overs.
</P>
<P>
The experts said the policy of encouraging debt roll-overs was
just a short-term palliative and did nothing to solve the
long-term problem. However, there still seems to be a reluctance
in providing any official support for debt restructuring along the
lines of Indonesia and South Korea, as there is fear it would
confirm how bad the situation really is.
</P>
<P>
This also highlights the need for the framework to be supported
by the international community, the experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
