<HEADLINE> Jobless Reach New High in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel's unemployment rate
reached 8.4 percent in the first quarter of the year, the highest
since the last quarter of 1993, triggering new debate over the
government's economic policy.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics available Wednesday, the unemployment
rate is 1 percent higher than that in the same period of last year
and 0.8 percent higher than that of the previous quarter. It means
some 189,000 people are without work.
</P>
<P>
The figures aroused a storm among politicians and labor
experts, partly because Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman has
recently said that the country's economy has begun to turn around.
</P>
<P>
Israeli newspapers quoted Labor and Social Affairs Minister
Eli Ishai as saying Tuesday that much of the blame lies with the
Bank of Israel's tight policy. Meanwhile, Immigration and
Absorption Minister Yuli Edelstein called on the government to
pump state funds into the workforce rather than improving the road
and rail infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
But Neeman rejected the criticism on the government's policies,
saying that the situation would be even worse without them. He
said the government would continue to allow the private sector to
develop and grow, to serve as an engine for the whole economy.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also strongly denies that its monetary policy
is the cause of the rise in the unemployment rate. It suggested
that the problem is structural, with many people falling victim to
the change from traditional industries to high-tech ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
