<HEADLINE> Over 1,000 Schools Hit By Pollution in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Pollution has become a serious
problem for 1,153 schools in 69 provinces across Thailand,
according to a survey by the Office of the National Primary
Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
The survey, whose results were made available on Wednesday,
revealed that 89 schools are affected by dust from quarries and
mines, 37 by dust from cement factories, 203 by dust from other
industrial factories, 45 by dust from mills, and 406 by road dust.
</P>
<P>
Up to 348 schools suffer from the stench and noise emitted by
nearby factories, and 25 from smoke that comes from burning wood
and rubbish.
</P>
<P>
In certain areas, the density of small-size dust in the air
reached 1,700 micrograms per cubic meter, five times the
acceptable standard.
</P>
<P>
Pupils and teachers have developed health problems such as
shortness of breath.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 out of 47 teachers at a primary school examined by
the Occupational Health Division were found to be suffering from
lung diseases and at the risk of developing tuberculosis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
