<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Automakers Propose Emission Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- European automobile manufacturers
on Wednesday handed the European Commission a new proposal for
carbon dioxide emission levels.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, made by the European Automobile Manufacturers
Association (ACEA), contained a carbon dioxide emission commitment
of 140 grams per kilometer of new passenger cars sold by ACEA
members in the European Union (EU) by the year 2008.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, adopted by the ACEA board last Thursday, also
addressed a number of other environmental concerns which the
commission had voiced.
</P>
<P>
The ACEA proposed reviewing in 2003 the possibilities for
moving further toward the 120 grams per kilometer target by 2012.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the EU's executive body, however, expects to
achieve an average carbon dioxide emission of 120 grams per
kilometer by 2005.
</P>
<P>
The ACEA proposal earlier did not contain any conditions that
caused concern to the commission and the European Council of
Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Union Environment Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard said, "We have
made substantial progress with the ACEA over the last few weeks,
but we are not there yet. There are a number of sticking points
where we still have to find solutions."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said the ACEA's claim on fuel quality forced
the automakers and the commission to postpone their final decision
on the ACEA proposal on carbon dioxide emission.
</P>
<P>
The European Council of Ministers and European Parliament are
expected to discuss and work out a fuel quality directive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
