<HEADLINE> Iran's Foreign Debts Drop Despite Lower Oil Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite a sharp fall in oil earnings
of the oil giant, Iran managed to reduce its foreign debts to
12.56 billion U.S. dollars by the end of 1997 from 16.8 billion
dollars in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the Central Bank of Iran (CBI) available
Wednesday showed that Iran's long- and medium-term foreign debts
stood at 9.68 billion dollars while its short-term debts were 2.88
billion dollars by end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, if contingent obligations, including opened letters of
credit not yet consigned and future interest, were taken into
account, Iran's total external debts would reach 24.5 billion
dollars, the CBI report said.
</P>
<P>
President of the CBI Mohsen Nourbakhsh said last month that
Iran enjoyed a favorable trade balance of 3.83 billion dollars in
the past Iranian year, ending March 20, with its total exports to
be 18.82 billion dollars, including 3 billion dollars from non-oil
exports.
</P>
<P>
Iran had expected to obtain 17.7 billion dollars from oil
exports in the past Iranian year, but failed to reach the goal due
to the sagging oil prices to below 12 dollars per barrel by March.
</P>
<P>
Iran earned 18.5 billion dollars in 1996 from oil exports when
oil price stood above 19 dollars per barrel, which enable it to
pay back some of its foreign debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
