<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review China's Macro Economic Indices Show Favorable Changes (1) by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released by the related
departments show that China's real estate sector has been
recovering quickly, with the national real estate index rising
above what is called the "prosperity line" in April.
</P>
<P>
This is good news to the Chinese government, which has called
on the country to shake off the consequences of the Asian
financial crisis and try to achieve an eight percent economic
growth rate this year.
</P>
<P>
For the past few months, China's economy has been operating
fairly smoothly. Although the inertial declining trend of the
economy has not yet been reversed, some advance indices of the
macro economy have shown favorable changes with the gradual
implementation of the central government's macro-economic control
measures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the central bank show that the decline in loans
has been basically stopped, with total loans rising by 153.75
billion yuan in the first four months, of which over 151 billion
yuan was added in March and April.
</P>
<P>
Medium and long-term loans increased more than 10 billion yuan
in April to reverse the declining trend in the previous three
months, indicating that the central bank's readjustment of monetary
policies has become effective.
</P>
<P>
The analysis by the State Statistics Bureau of the first four
months' economic development shows that the state's efforts in
expanding domestic demand through increased investment have achieved
results. National fixed assets investment in the first four months
reached 271.3 billion yuan, up 12.2 percent from the same period
last year, and the growth rate in April was as high as 15.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
What should be noticed is that investment in enterprises'
technological upgrading rose sharply, investment in central China
began to recover and many more new projects have been launched.
</P>
<P>
Increased investment has helped push up heavy industrial
production, which was up 7.7 percent in April, one percentage
point higher than in the first quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review China's Macro Economic Indices Show Favorable Changes (2) by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another point worth noticing is the growth of new consumption
areas. With the change in Chinese residents' consumption
structure, some new consumption areas have been formed, including
residential housing, automobiles, rural area consumption, social
services, information consumption and cultural consumption.
</P>
<P>
Experts share the view that these new areas will inject new
vigor into the development of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Noted Chinese economist Liu Guoguang said that the country has
favorable objective conditions to support its economic
growth. Transport, energy, raw materials, agriculture,
foreign exchange reserves, inflation rate and other critical
sectors are at their best time and capable of supporting a growth
rate higher than eight percent.
</P>
<P>
"We have a good reason to believe that, with the government's
fine-tuning measures taking effect, the declining trend of
the economic growth will gradually be stopped, and the economy is
expected to recover in the second half of this year or the first
half of next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he also pointed out that much needs to be done to solve
the current economic problems and difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shucheng from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences said
that, considering the present economic conditions, it is possible
to meet the eight percent growth target.
</P>
<P>
He said that the consequences of the Asian financial
crisis will inevitably weaken exports' contribution to the
economic growth. As a result, increased investment becomes a
critical factor in expanding domestic demand to push the
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"More efforts should be made to choose appropriate investment
projects and ensure increased investment be actually used by the
targeted projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that industrial development should be combined
with local characteristics to give full play to local growth
potential and avoid repetitive construction.
</P>
<P>
Experts agree that the government should make more minor
macro-economic readjustments in time to solve the current
difficulties and problems in the overall economic
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
