<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 25 Killed in German Train Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- At least 25 people were killed and 200
others wounded when a high-speed passenger train derailed
Wednesday morning at the rail station of the northeastern German
town of Eschede.
</P>
<P>
The Intercity-Express (ICE), the country's fastest train,
apparently hit a car which had plunged onto the rail tracks from
a bridge, the German news agency DPA quoted eyewitnesses as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The car had reportedly smashed through the crash barrier of the
road bridge and plunged onto the rail tracks in front of the
oncoming train.
</P>
<P>
The train, enroute from Munich to Hamburg, slammed into car
with a speed of at about 200 kilometers per hour, derailed and
smashed into the bridge support.
</P>
<P>
The entire structure of the bridge then collapsed, burying part
of the train under the rubble. All 13 carriages were telescoped
into one another, making it difficult for rescue workers to
retrieve the passengers trapped in the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
According to German rail authorities, the train has seats for
759 passengers. The number of people actually traveling in the
train is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be the worst rail accident in modern German
history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
