<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Important for Butterfly Collection: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Himalayan kingdom of Nepal
can be an important country for butterfly collection, where rich
species of butterflies have been found, Collin Phillip Smith, an
entomologist, said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 16,000 species of butterflies in the world, 640
species have been identified so far in Nepal, the official RSS
news agency Wednesday quoted Smith as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Natural History Museum in Pokhara, about 200 kilometers
northwest of Kathmandu, has a collection of 10,000 butterflies of
576 species found in Nepal and the rest of the world, the RSS
said.
</P>
<P>
Last year more than 10,000 foreign and Nepalese tourists
visited the museum established in 1965, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Natural Science Museum at Swoyambhu in Kathmandu has a
collection of all the indigenous butterflies in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Butterflies found in the southern Terai plain and the northern
Himalayas of Nepal differ in size and species. Some of them were
detected at an altitude of 17,000 feet (about 5,180 meters), the
RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese collectors spent up to 500 U.S. dollars for a male
butterfly and 100 dollars for a female one found in Nepal on
mountains 9,000 feet (2,740 meters) high, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
Smith said that he has collected samples of butterflies in 60
of the 75 districts in Nepal, and found 375 species in the
Kathmandu Valley and 300 in the Pokhara Valley.
</P>
<P>
The Briton has undertaken studies and research in butterflies
in Nepal for the past 25 years, and has five books to his credit,
the RSS added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
