<HEADLINE> Supporting Policies Encourage Coal Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China, the world's largest coal
producer, is urging the country's coal enterprises to export more
coal products by working out a series of favorable polices and
measures, in a bid to check the declining economic efficiency in
the sector.
</P>
<P>
To support coal exports, the Industrial and Commercial Bank of
China will offer the coal enterprises nationwide loans totaling
around three billion yuan, to alleviate their fund shortages, said
Zhang Baoming, head of the newly-organized Administration of the
Coal Industry,
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national coal export conference held here today,
the senior official added that the country will offer a nine
percent export rebate for the coal enterprises instead of the
present three percent.
</P>
<P>
The Administration will still cut export commissions for coal
enterprises by one third, in a bid to bring into full play the
initiatives of these enterprises to export more coal products.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that China is the world's largest coal
producer, turning out an annual 1.35 billion tons, or one third of
the world's total. The country has earned 5.4 billion US dollars
by exporting 150 million tons of coal over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
However, its annual coal export amount to only just over 3,000
tons, about six percent of the world's total coal trade volume,
and so there is a huge potential to tap.
</P>
<P>
China plans to export 35 million tons of coal this year, and 50
million tons by the year 2000. The expansion of coal exports will
make the sector open wider to the rest of the world, and will
promote its operation and management from being extensive to being
intensive, said the official.
</P>
<P>
At present, supply exceeds demand in coal markets both at home
and abroad. The dwindling demand for coal in Southeast Asian
countries last year has affected China's coal exports, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China will take all measures possible to
expand its coal market shares worldwide, particularly in Asia,
Europe and South America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
