<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke060359 -Pak Reiterates Readiness to Resume Dialogue with India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan on Wednesday reiterated his country's readiness to
resume dialogue with India and called for multilateral efforts for
an early solution to the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Multilateral efforts are required to solve the core and
fundamental issue of Jammu and Kashmir which has led to
nuclearization of South Asia, said Gohar during a meeting with
Japanese Ambassador to Pakistan Minoru Kubota, according to an
official press release.
</P>
<P>
Gohar stressed that Pakistan was compelled to conduct nuclear
tests in order to protect its national security which was
"threatened" by India's nuclear program and "belligerent
statements" emanating from the Indian leadership.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he appreciated the concern Japan had shown about
Pakistan's security and emphasized the need to further strengthen
the mutually-beneficial ties between Pakistan and Japan.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Japanese ambassador reiterated his
government's proposal of hosting a meeting between India and
Pakistan in Tokyo to solve the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
He informed Gohar that Japanese leaders had said that the
Kashmir issue was the root cause of the problem in South Asia and
the United Nations General Assembly should help resolve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese ambassador on Wednesday also called on Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who said on the occasion that his
country had no choice but to rectify the strategic imbalance in
the region because Indian nuclear explosions had created serious
threats to the security of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
According to another press release issued by the government,
Pakistan has formally welcomed the Japanese proposal to host a
meeting between Pakistan and India on the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad on Wednesday told
the Japanese ambassador at the Foreign Office that Pakistan
appreciates that Japan has taken the lead and focused on the root
cause of tensions and the necessity of a just settlement of the
Kashmir dispute which alone can promote peace and stability in
South Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
