<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Acts to Ease Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will create at least
100,000 jobs in the next 18 months to ease the rising
unemployment, which hit a 14-year high of 3.9 percent, Financial
Secretary Donald Tsang said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our employment prospects in the foreseeable future are
positive. More jobs will go around," Tsang said after chairing a
meeting of a government employment task force.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force on Employment met for the first time here
Wednesday to address the unemployment problem and explore ways of
creating jobs in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Tsang stressed that tackling unemployment requires concerted,
collective and continued efforts from the government, the business
sector and the community.
</P>
<P>
"... there is no panacea in tackling unemployment. This is
likely to be a long battle," he said. "The answer to the
unemployment problem, both here in Hong Kong and elsewhere, lies
with economic recovery."
</P>
<P>
During the three months up to April 1998, the jobless rate in
Hong Kong soared to 3.9 percent, the highest since 1984. It stood
at 3.5 percent in the first quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force on Employment met to assess the potential
employment opportunities as a result of the government's major
policy initiatives, infrastructure development and public works.
</P>
<P>
It said in an assessment report that the Special Administrative
Region government will be able to offer 11,000 posts at all levels
in the civil service in the current financial year which ends in
March 1999. The remaining 89,000 new jobs will be created by the
private sector and non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Tsang also unveiled a package of 12
measures aimed at creating more jobs, strengthening employment
services, enhancing training and retraining, promoting further
education and combating illegal employment.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure development, which is expected to involve a
total investment of 235 billion HK dollars (30 billion U.S.
dollars) over the next five years, will generate 40,600 jobs in
the upcoming 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will boost its spending on
labor-intensive maintenance works, advance commencement of public
works, and speed up the construction of environmental projects in
an attempt to provide more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Set up in April 1998, the Task Force on Employment comprises
senior government officials and representatives from the business
and employee sectors, the academia and training institutions. The
financial secretary said the task force would meet regularly and
work hard with all concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
