<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ANKARA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading Turkish newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Aksam (Evening):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Ambassador to France Sonmez Koksal Tuesday presented
to French Foreign Ministry a note of protest against France's formal
recognition of the killings of ethnic Armenians by Turks in 1915 as genocide.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- The Higher Military Council, the supreme executive of the
Turkish Armed Force, has decided to hold a meeting on June 16 to
discuss some officers' involvement in gang and fundamentalist activities.
</P>
<P>
The generals are also expected to voice their dissatisfaction
with the coalition government's weakness in fighting the religious radicals.
</P>
<P>
Sabah (Morning):
</P>
<P>
-- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos has confirmed that
he will meet with his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem at the Balkan
foreign ministerial meeting to be held on June 8 and 9 in Istanbul, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Foreign Ministry said Tuesday that Ankara is ready to
start an investigation into the allegations that Turkey was involved
in the transfer of the Nazi gold looted from Jews during the Second
World War.
</P>
<P>
A New York times report has said that Turkey, which was a
neutral state in the war, played a role in helping Germany dispose
the gold. 
</P>
