<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Toughens Measures to Protest Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIRUT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Any one found to have cut down a tree
without approval in Lebanon would be jailed and fined up to 10,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Agriculture Ministry has drafted a bill containing
strict regulations on protecting trees that are threatened by
increasing haphazard building work in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The bill, the first of such type in the country, forbids falling
any tree without the approval from the ministry, according to a
ministry statement available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If the bill is passed, any violator would face a prison sentence
up to three years, with a fine of up to 15 million Lebanese pounds
(about 10,000 U.S. dollars) for each tree that has been cut down or
uprooted, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, any type of public work must be preceded by an
assessment of its damage to the environment.
</P>
<P>
In exceptional cases, the ministry would give approval with the
proviso that the builders replant trees within its boundaries under
strict guidelines and supervision.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the creation of the bill "was prompted by the
treat of deforestation" that kept growing with economic activities
after the end of the civil war in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is concerned with a sudden expansion of villages,
the construction of wide roads through forested areas, and the
threat of landslides and pollution, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
