<HEADLINE> Russian PM to Visit France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko will begin a two-day visit to France on Wednesday to
enhance economic ties between the countries.
</P>
<P>
Local media said that the visit by Kiriyenko is apparently
aimed at re-establishing the credit of Russia in the eyes of
international investors, as the country is experiencing a serious
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The visit will be Kiriyenko's first trip abroad since he took
office in April.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko will meet with President Jacques Chirac and Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin on Wednesday evening, and will co-chair
with Jospin a session of the Russian-French joint economic
committee on bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Paris, Kiriyenko said that Russia wishes to
reinforce its economic relations with France.
</P>
<P>
Besides bilateral relations, Kiriyenko is also expected to
discuss with French leaders the provision of financial aid to
Russia by the most industrialized nations of the G-7 group.
</P>
<P>
France, which registered a 5.5 billion franc (900 million
U.S. dollar) deficit in its trade with Russia in 1997, also wishes
to expand its economic cooperation with Russia in energy and other
fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
