<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Trading Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
trading stronger Wednesday but was well off its intraday highs
after strong growth data failed to inflame buyers.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended the local session at 61.66 U.S. cents
after closing at 61.23 here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Australian Bureau of Statistics
revealed gross domestic product (GDP) rising by a seasonally
adjusted 1.3 percent for the March quarter, for an annual growth
of 4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The result had economic growth steaming ahead of expectations
in the first three months of 1998, despite the threat from the
economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the very strong number, the Australian dollar really
still remained very bearish," Rothschild Australia treasury
manager Paul Macarounas said.
</P>
<P>
Market participants took on board comments by analysts that the
headline figure of a 1.3-percent rise was very misleading because
of a build-up in business inventories.
</P>
<P>
HSBC Markets chief economist John Edwards said the figures
portrayed an economy where consumption spending and investment
were flat and domestic final demand was negative (down 0.3 percent
in the quarter) for the first time in many years.
</P>
<P>
He added that if it were not for the buildup of stocks, the
expenditure measure would also have been negative.
</P>
<P>
Macarounas also said a major local bank appeared to be active
in the market, selling Australian dollars for a Japanese concern.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar has of late been tracking the fortunes of
the yen and traders said that would continue for some time.
</P>
<P>
Commodity prices is also a negative factor weighing on the
Australian dollar, and while both the yen and the gold price have
improved over the past 24 hours, traders said neither was out of
the woods yet.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended the day here at 84.90 from 85.32
against the Japanese yen and at 1.0947 from 1.0906 against the
German mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
