<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Strives for Customs Flexibility, Simplicity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Wednesday requested European legislators and government officials
to make customs code more flexible and simple.
</P>
<P>
In a report sent to the European Parliament and the European
Council of Ministers, the commission stressed that efforts must
chiefly be concentrated on organizing and coordinating national
systems so that existing customs rules may be better applied.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the European Union, urged
amendment of the basic regulation for the sake of greater
flexibility, specially in such matters as customs debt, and for
the sake of simplicity of formalities for customs declaration.
</P>
<P>
The European Union codified its customs law in 1993 when
hundreds of legal instruments were replaced with significant
improvements in transparency and simplicity.
</P>
<P>
The commission claimed to have taken several steps to improve
the efficiency of customs policy, both for the uniform application
of customs rules and for protecting the European Union's financial
interests.
</P>
<P>
It proposed to the legislators and government officials that
there should be more flexibility relating to the requirement to
submit certain accompanying documents with the goods declaration
in order to remove an obstacle to the computerization of customs
clearance procedures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
