<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos, Cabinet Set to Meet with President-Elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his regular press conference in the presidential palace,
Ramos said during the meeting, they will discuss the country's
macro economic situation and the status of major infrastructure
projects.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled meeting is part of a series of briefings that
kicked off on June 1 for the incoming administration to ensure the
continuity of government programs and a smooth transfer of power
on June 30.
</P>
<P>
"We want the Estrada administration to be more successful -- if
we can be called successful -- than this administration because
that will mean the building up of Philippine well-being and the
quality of life," Ramos said at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, Estrada and other officials of the incoming
government attended a briefing on the country's security situation
and the modernization program of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Estrada is currently the vice president of the country. He won
a landslide victory in the May 11 elections as the standard bearer
of the main opposition, the Laban ng Makabayang Masang Pilipino
(Fight of Patriotic Filipino Masses).
</P>
<P>
Ramos was banned by law to seek a second term. He would step
down when his six-year single term expires on June 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Implements National Software Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China has begun to implement a
universal supervision system for technological standards of all
computer software produced in the country.
</P>
<P>
A relevant government institute issued the first group of
certificates of registration to 23 software products of 24 local
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from the Ministry of the Information
Industry, the national software registration system is aimed at
creating a fair market environment for software manufacturers in
the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the registration system is not a copyright system.
</P>
<P>
Under the registration system, The government examines every
software product to see whether it has the technological
characteristics that the manufacturer claims, and, if it has,
whether these functions comply with national standards.
</P>
<P>
The software that passes the examination will receive certificates
of competence.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said that the registration system will help
users choose among various software products.
</P>
<P>
At present, the National Software Products Administration
Center is the government institute in charge of the examination
and registration work.
</P>
<P>
China's computer industry has expanded at an annual rate of
more than 50 percent for the past seven consecutive years. Sales
of PCs totaled 3.5 million items in China last year. In the same
period, the local software industry grew by over 30 percent per
year, with the local software market exceeding 11 billion yuan
(about 1.3 billion US dollars)-worth in 1997. China now has five
national software production centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Train Crash Kills at Least 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 people were killed and
many others wounded when a high-speed passenger train derailed
Wednesday in a rail station in the northeastern German town of
Eschede, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred before 11 a.m. (local time) when the
Intercity-Express, the country's fastest train, was on the way to
Hamburg from Munich.
</P>
<P>
The train jumped tracks when traveling at a speed of about 200
kilometers an hour, slamming into the base of a road bridge. About
13 cars went off the tracks.
</P>
<P>
The death toll has not been officially confirmed and the
wounded are being airlifted by helicopters to nearby hospitals.
</P>
<P>
About 400 rescue workers at the scene were trying to retrieve
the injured from the wreckage. They were having difficulties
reaching the injured because the bridge had collapsed onto the
telescoped carriages.
</P>
<P>
So far, the cause of the accident is still unknown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
