<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Not Rules Out Increase in Defense Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha
said Wednesday that India does not rule out any increase in the
defense budget in the future if it is warranted.
</P>
<P>
Talking to foreign journalists here, he said no country could
afford to ignore its national security concerns. The 14-percent
increase in the defense allocation in the 1998-99 budget,
presented to the parliament on Monday, is meager as it is mostly
to take care of the inflation and growth.
</P>
<P>
Turning to nuclear weaponization, he said it would be financed
out of the funds provided in the budget for the defense research
and development organization.
</P>
<P>
India conducted five nuclear tests on May 11 and 13 and has a
plan for nuclear weaponization, which have been denounced by the
world community.
</P>
<P>
Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes told the on-going
Upper House session Wednesday that the government has approved the
next phase of the 2,500-kilometer long-range missile Agni for
developing a longer-range missile system in the country. The
present Agni project has been completed.
</P>
<P>
He said an integrated guided missiles development program
undertaken by the defense research and development organization in
June 1983 for the design, development and limited production of
four missile systems -- Perithvi, Trishul, Akash, Nag -- and a
re-entry technology demonstration project of Agni is in progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
