<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Downward Trend Persists in Australian Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- An improvement in gold and
resource stocks and strong economic growth figures Wednesday
failed to reverse this week's downward trend on the Australian
sharemarket.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 9.1 points to 2662.0 in tepid
trade, with a weakening of the Japanese market providing another
dampener for local sentiment.
</P>
<P>
"It looked good this morning but the information we got has
hurt the market, plus we had the rally yesterday afternoon," said
Steve Negrine from Reynolds and Co.
</P>
<P>
"No one is enthusiastic. It's difficult to get anyone keen
about buying in this market."
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was down 24.9 points at 4625.6, with
banking stocks generally weaker after stronger than expected
growth figures severely damaged hopes for a cut in official
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Growth of 1.3 percent in the March quarter was higher than
market expectations.
</P>
<P>
"The GDP figure showed a bit of growth and counts out any more
rate cuts," Negrine said.
</P>
<P>
ANZ fell 24 cents to 10.77 Australian dollars after going
ex-dividend, while Westpac dropped 5.2 cents and Colonial added
eight cents.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said that major institution Merrill Lynch was a late
seller in several major stocks.
</P>
<P>
Global media giant News Corp added one cent while its preferred
shares were four cents stronger.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished 5.1 points higher at 1085.1
after Tuesday's heavy fall.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto rose 35 cents to 19.30 Australian dollars while BHP
shed one cent to 13.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index retraced some of Tuesday's losses, rising 22.3
points as the bullion price surged and closed 6.70 U.S. dollars
higher at 294.35.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 257.2 million shares, worth 789.9 million
Australian dollars (489.73 million U.S. dollars), with falls of
652 outnumbering rises of 396, while 404 stocks were steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
