<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Link Smoking to Hearing Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A five-year study of 3,753
people of the age 48 to 92 found that smokers are 1.7 times as
likely to suffer from hearing loss than nonsmokers, the Journal of
the American Medical Association said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The more people smoked, the greater their risk of hearing loss,
said the study, funded by the National Institute on Aging and
conducted by researchers at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
Karen Cruickshanks, leading researcher of the study, reported
that people who smoked an average of a pack a day for 40 years
were 1.3 times as likely to have a hearing loss as those who
smoked a pack a day for a decade.
</P>
<P>
She also said that nonsmokers who lived with smokers were
almost twice as likely to have hearing loss than those who were
not exposed to smoke at home.
</P>
<P>
Of the participants between the ages of 60 and 69, the results
of the study showed that 35.3 percent of nonsmokers suffered a
hearing loss, compared with 47.3 percent of ex-smokers and 56.4
percent of current smokers.
</P>
<P>
Dr. John Leonetti, a professor at Loyola University Medical
Center in Maywood who specializes in the study of ear-related
disorders, said doctors like himself already believed smoking
could cause hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
Whether smoking actually contributes to hearing loss is still
unclear. To confirm the link, the study's authors are now
conducting a five-year follow-up study, in which they are tracking
hearing changes among smokers and nonsmokers in order to determine
if a direct cause-and-effect relationship exists.
</P>
<P>
Hearing loss is estimated to affect 30 to 35 percent of adults
aged 65 to 75 years old in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
