<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Chinese City Goes From Noisy To Quiet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- People who are used to the noise
of a city may be surprised on the streets of Nanning, the capital
of south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Some residents call it a miracle, it's as if they were suddenly
thrown into a different world on September 1, 1997, when drivers
were prohibited from blowing their horns in this city of 1.28
million people, 63 percent of whom are members of the Zhuang
ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
Nanning has an area of only 84 square kilometers, with 220,000
motor vehicles, 144,000 of them motorcycles. To this number are
added 1.3 million bicycles and a large number of vehicles from
outside the city, all crammed into the narrow streets, leading to
a lot of honking, which has had a bad effect on local citizens.
</P>
<P>
"My house is near the road," one person complains, "so to deal
with the noise, my son has to close the windows to do his
homework, even on hot days."
</P>
<P>
China has had a noise law since March, 1997, and since
September of 1997, Nanning has sought to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
A recent study showed the average noise level on the city's
main streets having dropped from 74 decibels to 69.9 decibels,
making Nanning one of the most successful cities in reducing the
honking.
</P>
<P>
Reducing the amount of noise coming from construction sites,
factories and residential areas was another task of the Nanning
Environment Protection Bureau, which last year reinforced
restrictions at 220 major constrution sites.
</P>
<P>
It even stopped constrution work near schools during the annual
entrance examinations last summer, a move that was highly praised
by teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's efforts brought Nanning's average noise volume
down to 57.8 decibels in 1997, much lower than the national level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
