<HEADLINE> Files of Confucian Temple's Relics Getting Better Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Qufu city in east China, the
birthplace of Confucius, is using a computerized file system to
manage historic and cultural relics at the Confucian Temple.
</P>
<P>
The city is the first to use a computer system in a Chinese
historic site, by applying five million yuan worth of
U.S. technology.
</P>
<P>
The Confucian Temple, in Shandong Province, has an array of
ancient buildings in the style of the Jin, Yuan, Ming and Qing
dynasties (1115-1911), built by imperial families to pay homage to
Confucius, one of the most famous philosophers and educators in
ancient China.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there are more than 280,000 relics that date back
to the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220 A.D.), like stone engravings,
inscriptions, tombs and files and documents. Of them, 10,000
have been logged on the computer, according to Li Bozhu, a
technician at the computer center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
