<HEADLINE> Singapore PM Calls for Asia-Pacific Information Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong Wednesday urged the creation of an Asia-Pacific information
society to timely reap the benefits of convergence for the
Asia-Pacific's role in the global information society.
</P>
<P>
"It is a bold vision to create an Asia-Pacific information
society," Goh said in his opening address at the Third APEC
Ministerial Meeting for Telecommunications and the Information
Industry.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that "the vision will not only have the
development of telecommunications and information technology but
also the society of the future."
</P>
<P>
The arrival of an information era will have great consequences
"far more significant than we could ever imagine," he said.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunication ministers and their representatives from APEC
members are attending the meeting whose theme is "Realizing the
Asia-Pacific Information Society."
</P>
<P>
Goh urged Asian economies struggling in the economic crisis not
to hesitate in making efforts to develop the telecommunications
and information industry. "Some economies may not give priority to
prepare for the advent of the Asia-Pacific information society.
but they would pay a price for the delay," he warned.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that the "financial crisis has shown how crucial
it is for us to deal with the challenges of an increasingly
interdependent and networked global environment." "Our markets
have become so interlinked that the difficulties one economy faces
invariably affect other economies," he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Asia is reeling from an economic crisis, the prime
minister also said, "This crisis is partly brought about by
globalization and the revolutionary changes in telecommunications
and information technology." 
</P>
