<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Archives' "Guardian Spirits" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- In a spacious workroom not far from
the Lhasa River, 74-year-old Ngawang Qoida, the eldest archivist
of the Archives of Tibetan History, sits cross-legged on a
cushion, busy with his daily work, arranging stacks of archives.
</P>
<P>
Official documents are a major part of the Archives' files,
which are crucial to Tibetan historical research, he says.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan History Archives now has more than three million files
from the Tibetan regional government, since Tibet was officially
incorporated into China in the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368).
</P>
<P>
The Archives houses a fifth of the country's total archives
concerning Tibet, including letters and official documents
exchanged between the central and Tibetan regional governments,
imperial edicts and decrees, and reports to the emperors from the
regional governments.
</P>
<P>
The Archives has a staff of 100 people, the older ones are all
specialists in Tibetan language and history, and many of the
younger ones have received professional training in categorization
and conservation of archives.
</P>
<P>
Workers began rescuing Tibetan archives in 1959 when the
central government provided manpower and money to collect more
than three million volumes and over 400 gunnysacks of files, most
of them quite worn and scattered about in different regional
government agencies, official residences, and monasteries.
</P>
<P>
The Archives was completed in 1984, and began using microfilm
in 1990, thanks to President Jiang Zemin, who noticed, after a
visit to Tibet, that the Archives was still using primitive
methods in its filing system.
</P>
<P>
The microfilm has greatly prolonged the life of historical
files and made the use of archival resources possible, according
to Dagwa, a microphotography technician of the first generation at
the Archives. Some 140,000 volumes of historical files are now on
microfilm.
</P>
<P>
And Zhouga, the director of the Archives, says, "People like
Ngawang Qoida are really the guardian spirits of Tibet's
historical files, and they have contributed quite a lot to the
conservation of Tibet's archives." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Provides Credit Facility to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF)has released 53 million U.S. Dollars to Zimbabwe following
its executive board's approval of the country's request for 176
million U.S. Dollars stand-by credit facility.
</P>
<P>
In a statement faxed from Washington, the IMF said that the
next tranche of 18 million U.S. Dollars would be released in
mid-August subject to the Zimbabwean government's meeting the set
targets by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
"The International Monetary Fund's Executive Board approved on
June 1, 1998, a thirteen-month stand-by arrangement for Zimbabwe
equivalent to special drawing rights (SDR) 130.5 million or 176
million U.S. Dollars," the Zimbabwe News Agency Tuesday quoted
the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The first tranche under the arrangement equivalent to 39.1
million SDR or 53 million U.S. Dollars has been disbursed,"the
IMF said.
</P>
<P>
Three additional tranches of 35 million U.S. Dollars each
would be disbursed in mid-November and in the middle of February
and May 1999 subject to the country's economic performance at the
end of September and December 1998 and March next year.
</P>
<P>
Following the approval, an IMF team is expected in Harare in
July to start discussions on a three-year enhanced structural
adjustment facility (ESAF) which could replace the stand-by
arrangement before its expiry.
</P>
<P>
ESAF will also provide the country larger access to IMF
resources on concessional terms.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe desperately needs an injection of foreign currency to
improve its balance-of-payments position and kick-start the
second phase of economic reforms, the Zimbabwe program for
economic and social transformation (ZIMPREST).
</P>
<P>
The IMF, the world's lender of last resort, suspended crucial
financial aid to Zimbabwe in September 1995 because of what was
seen as the government's fiscal indiscipline.
</P>
<P>
However, in interviews with the Zimbabwe News Agency,
economists and market analysts said that the latest IMF move was
just a short-term measure and warned that the country could miss
the set targets if it does not urgently restore macro-economic
stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
