<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Resume Drug Export to Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will resume export of
manufactured pharmaceutical products to Ghana next month, 10
years after it was banned by the Ghanaian authorities.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the export was made possible by the lifting
of the ban by Ghana in November 1996 after bilateral talks, the
Guardian newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It added that officials of the Ghanaian Food and Drugs Board
had given a favorable assessment of Nigeria's drug manufacturing
facilities early this year.
</P>
<P>
Official sources at the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Group of
the Manufacturers Association of Nigeria (PMGMAN) estimated that
Nigeria will be able to export 500 million Naira (about five
million U.S. Dollars) worth of drugs to Ghana in the third
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
It was also estimated that export to Ghana will boost the
capacity utilization of Nigeria's pharmaceutical sector from the
current 20 percent to about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Valentine Ofili, the executive secretary of the PMGMAN, was
quoted as saying that a symposium and exhibition will be held in
Ghanaian capital Accra from July 14 to 17 for the promotion of
drugs made in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
About 30 Nigerian firms will attend the event organized by a
Ghanaian consultancy firm, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
