<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hospital Registration Number Deal Exposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangming Daily reports on
cases involving the illegal selling of registration numbers at
Tongren Hospital, a nationally-known eye disease hospital.
</P>
<P>
One of the paper's reporters went to the hospital, in downtown
Beijing, recently around 5 o'clock in the morning and found about
300 people waiting at the registration office.
</P>
<P>
"Do you want to jump the queue?" one man came over and asked
him.
</P>
<P>
"Sure, but how?" was his answer.
</P>
<P>
"If you give 100 yuan, you can get expert's registration below
the 50th place, 30 yuan will get a place between 50 and 80, and 10
yuan will get an ordinary doctor," was the reply.
</P>
<P>
"We'll see to it that you get registered. If not, you don't
pay," the seller added.
</P>
<P>
At around 7 o'clock, when the registration window was about to
open, a man who claimed to be a hospital employee came out and
told the crowd, "Those with numbers come first and queue up, all
others please form another queue."
</P>
<P>
So, the people who paid the illegal fee got priority in
registering, while those who didn't, no matter how early they
came, had to wait.
</P>
<P>
After several of these media exposure, the hospital
administration began to take steps to stop this by warning
patients.
</P>
<P>
However, some people still seem to be ready to pay the sellers,
and many others are ready to come queue up as early as 3 or 4 in
the morning, the hospital authorities say. The local police
station says that it has also got involved to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
But, the reporter say, neither the hospital authorities nor the
local police have really been as effective as they claim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Report New Impotence Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Two experimental drugs that can
be taken orally look like promising alternatives to Viagra for the
treatment of male erectile dysfunction (MED), U.S. scientists
reported.
</P>
<P>
In a study of an experimental drug called Phentolamine or
Vasomax, about 37 percent of men with mild to moderate impotence
responded to a 40 milligram dose and 45 percent responded to an 80
milligram dose, reported Dr. Irwin Goldstein, a professor of
surgery at Boston University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Viagra, Phentolamine could safely be used by men taking
nitrates -- such as nitroglycerin -- for heart disease, said
Goldstein, adding that the major side effect of the drug was nasal
congestion.
</P>
<P>
The drug will be available in the United States in a year or
so, the doctor estimated.
</P>
<P>
Another impotence drug, apomorphine, is designed to be taken
under the tongue. In a study of 457 patients, 60 percent of men
taking a six milligram dose of the drug achieved an erection firm
enough for intercourse, reported Dr. Harin Padma-Nathan of the
University of Southern California Medical School.
</P>
<P>
"The most common adverse event was nausea, which was mild in
most cases and was associated with a high degree of habituation
people got used to it," Dr. Padma-Nathan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Industries to Be Upgraded in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- North China's Tianjin municipality,
an old industrial base dominated by processing industries, is to
spend 26.1 billion yuan (3.14 billion US dollars) in upgrading 160
major projects involving new high-technologies in the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
The plan was drafted in a bid to improve the quality of major
products made by large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises
and making 20 percent of the technology and equipment in these
enterprises to comply with the advanced world standards, a local
official explained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tianjin hopes to further improve the industrial
structure of automobile, machine-building, electronic and
metallurgical industries, and to produce more well-selling
manufactured goods.
</P>
<P>
The city has worked out policies to encourage large and
medium-sized state-owned enterprises to upgrade traditional
industries with imported high-tech, and to raise technology of
industrial production and in-depth processing standards, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the city has included micro-electronics, laser,
bio-engineering, new energy and new materials into its list
of development priority, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing enterprises in Tianjin turned out 160 kinds of
new products as a result of applying new, high-technologies and
generated an additional output value of 16.5 billion yuan (1.99
billion US dollars) in 1997, said the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
