<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xi'an Ups Investment to Ensure Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- This capital of northwest China's
Shaanxi Province has decided to increase investment to ensure that
it hits its economic growth target for this year.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, the largest city in Northwest China, has reported an
annual economic growth rate of more than 14 percent for six
consecutive years, and it aims for the same growth rate this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest official statistics show that Xi'an's gross
domestic product grew 10.6 percent in the first quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the relative economic slowdown to
insufficient demand, and significant drops in exports and foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the successful realization of the targeted economic
growth rate, Xi'an will increase its investment in infrastructure
in the remaining months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The city's fixed-assets investment is planned at 14.8 billion
yuan for the April-December period, a surge of 26.6 percent over
the corresponding period of last year. Of this amount, 10.26
billion yuan will be invested in infrastructure facilities, the
rural economy and the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an has also decided to take measures to stimulate
consumption, with planned investment in real estate fixed at 2.24
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The capital of several dynasties, Xi'an also plans to receive
500,000 overseas tourists this year, with tourism-based foreign
exchange earnings targeted at 210 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark Suspends Health Grants to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Danish government has
suspended grants worth 36 million U.S. Dollars to Uganda due to
the mismanagement of the funds.
</P>
<P>
An official in the health ministry was quoted by Wednesday's
New Vision paper as saying that the suspension is not true. But
Deputy Danish Ambassador to Uganda Jens K. Rasmussen confirmed
the suspension.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat said the grants will only be released till there
has been fundamental improvement in fund management in the
ministry of health.
</P>
<P>
"We have temporarily stopped our health sector grants because
we have been having problems with mismanagement which we are
trying to address. We hope for further dialog on the matter with
the ministry of health," he said.
</P>
<P>
The suspension is reportedly to have affected several big
national health programs and grants to some districts. An order
for drug kits for 1,400 clinics throughout the country has been
stopped.
</P>
<P>
The decision came at a time when the ministry of health is
grappling with mismanagement of the funds.
</P>
<P>
An internal audit, the report said, revealed that millions of
U.S. Dollars were spent on a conference in a hotel in Gulu
district which did not exist. But the bill was paid out of the
Danish funds.
</P>
<P>
Another audit said that the National Medical Stores (NMS)
could not account for some 1.2 million U.S. Dollars purportedly
banked between March 1996 and January 1998. And even some
transactions were conducted through a Dollar bank account which
did not exist in NMS records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
