<HEADLINE> Kenya, Russia to Act on Direct Export of Flowers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Russia are working out
modalities to facilitate direct export of Kenya's flowers to
Moscow, the Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho has said.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government was addressing the export policies with
Russia to solve obstacles which hinder the entrance of more local
products to the Russian market, Wednesday's Kenya Times quoted
Kamotho as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The trade minister noted that the high quality flowers
produced in the east African country could gain a wider market in
Moscow and other cities in Russia if exported directly without
going through Holland.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when he received a delegation led by Juriy
Kotow, President of the Moscow Chamber of Commerce and Industry,
who paid a courtesy call on the minister.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the trade volume between the two countries which
stands at the level of 16 million U.S. Dollars, the minister said
that it has been negligible compared with trade between Kenya and
her principle trade partners.
</P>
<P>
Kotow told the Kenyan minister that his delegation was in
Nairobi to explore business opportunities, saying that "we have
come to Kenya with projects and ideas to discuss with our Kenyan
counterparts."
</P>
<P>
He said that major Russian companies are studying the
possibilities of setting up joint ventures in assembly plants for
motorcycles, bicycles and other accessories.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is a potentially good market for Russian goods, said
Kotow, adding that his country is willing to supply Kenya with
drugs, trucks and drilling machines.
</P>
<P>
The current visit by the Russians followed last year's meeting
between Moscow Mayor Y.V. Luozkov and Kenyan former Foreign
Minister Kalonzo Musyoka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
