<HEADLINE> Dalian Economic Development Zone Expands Hi-Tech Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The economic and technological
development zone of Dalian, a port city in northeast China's
Liaoning Province, has been practicing preferential policies to
develop high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
One preferential policy announced recently stipulates that
high-tech enterprises will be given a wide range of preferential
treatment, including tax rebates on added value if they market
their own commodities, and exemption from tax levies on business
earnings generated by technological activities such as
technological transfer, consultancy and other technological
service, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
To support industrialization of high-tech enterprises, the
development zone has also decided to earmark 20 million yuan
annually for a scientific and technological progress fund
beginning from this year.
</P>
<P>
It will also set aside one percent of its revenue each year for
a scientific and technological risk investment fund, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Dalian Economic and Technological Development Zone, 27.5 km
away from the downtown area of Dalian City, covers a total area of
24 sq km. It was approved as a national-level economic and
technological development zone in September 1984 and began
construction in October of the same year.
</P>
<P>
By September 1997, businessmen from 40 countries and regions
have invested in the zone and have started more than 1,000
overseas-funded businesses, with the paid-in volume of overseas
investment amounting to 2.49 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
There are also more than 7,000 domestically-funded enterprises
in the zone, with their registered investment standing at 10.1
billion yuan, said local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
