<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Nuclear Industry Gives Priority to Civilian Application (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China's nuclear industry is
stepping up its shift from military production to civilian
application and is becoming a new powerhouse of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
China's nuclear industry is now operating under a new system
featuring a combination of military and civilian production,
development of nuclear electric power and a diversified economy,
with nuclear technology as the foundation, said a senior official
with the China Nuclear Industry Corp.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the nuclear sector has established a
large number of enterprise groups over the past few years in the
economically-developed coastal areas such as Shanghai in east
China and Guangdong province in south China, and has developed
more than 1,500 kinds of civilian products.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear industrial economy has been expanding in China by
maintaining a high growth rate in a succession of years, resulting
in remarkable improvement in the country's comprehensive economic
strength.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output of civilian products now makes up over 80
percent of China's nuclear industrial output, which is 20 times
the total when adjusting efforts first began.
</P>
<P>
Development of nuclear power is a major way for the industry to
make strategic adjustments, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Station of east China's Zhejiang and
the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station in south China's Guangdong
province have been operating safely.
</P>
<P>
The two nuclear power stations have not only alleviated
electric power shortages in east China and Guangdong, but also
have transmitted a large quantity of power to Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
