<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cannabis Called Serious Problem in Northern NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Cannabis grown in Northland,
northern New Zealand, earns over 700 million New Zealand dollars
(370 million U.S. dollars) a year in street value and possibly
much more, a New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) report said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a study by Auckland University as claiming that
cannabis from the region generates a cash turnover much greater
than its dairy industry, which earned around 400 million dollars
(220 million U.S. dollars) in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The study also finds that many rural communities and towns in
Northland rely on cannabis money to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
Cannabis is a means of survival for many Maori families
struggling in poverty, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It is common in Northland for children as young as 10 to smoke
cannabis. NZPA quoted a health worker in the region as saying that
of 56 children she spoke with in one school, 54 were cannabis
users.  
</P>
</TEXT>
