<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Nuclear Industry Gives Priority to Civilian Application (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two nuclear power stations, which are now under commercial
operation, have both been economically viable. Per-capita annual
output of the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station is more than 4
million yuan, while per-capita annual output of the first phase of
the Qinshan Nuclear Power Station exceeds 700,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Practice has proved that the investment return rate of nuclear
power is not lower than that of coal-burning electric power
stations. The nuclear industry with power development as its main
feature has become a new powerhouse of China's national economy.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the second and third phases of Qinshan, and the
Ling'ao and Lianyungang nuclear power stations are all in full
swing.
</P>
<P>
By early next century China's nuclear power generating capacity
should amount to 9.2 million kilowatts and, by then, earnings from
sales of nuclear power are expected to reach 30 billion yuan a
year. The industrial structure of the country's nuclear industry
will be further improved at that point, coupled with improved
economy and technology.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power now contributes one percent of China's total
power output, but nuclear power makes up 17 percent of the world's
total power output. Clean and highly efficient, nuclear power has
advantages in the market based on a range of factors such as
energy structure, the environment and transportation.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, Fujian and Jiangxi provinces of east China, Hainan
province of south China and Hunan province of central-south China
have all been active in making preparations for constructing their
own nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
In the next century, China is expected to have a significant
development in nuclear power. By the year 2010 China's nuclear
power-generating capacity will reach 20 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
And by 2020, China's nuclear power-generating capacity should
reach 40 million kilowatts and the proportion of nuclear power in
the country's total power production should increase to five
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
