<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Universities Strengthening Student Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese universities and colleges
have recently taken more measures to enhance students' confidence
in the country's future, the Education Ministry has said.
</P>
<P>
Most universities and colleges have offered Deng Xiaoping
Theory course to help students obtain correct understandings of
the country's reform and opening up process, ministry sources told
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
A cadre of the Beijing University Committee of the Communist
Youth League said that the course is welcomed by many students
because "it explains what is socialism and how to build socialism".
</P>
<P>
"Deng Xiaoping Theory is a system that reflects the real
national situations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many universities and colleges have held seminars on hot
subjects, such as Chinese economy and Sino-US
relations. Established economists, diplomats, journalists and even
senior government officials have been invited to give lectures.
</P>
<P>
"We are paying great attention to both Chinese and foreign
affairs, and most students like to read newspapers very much,"
said a student working for the Student Union of Beijing
University. "Now we are especially interested in President
Clinton's China tour," he said.
</P>
<P>
An Education Ministry official said that all Chinese
universities and colleges are making great efforts to improve
students' morale and develop campus culture.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, universities and colleges have launched campaigns
to spread the popularity of Beijing Opera. The move is expected to
enhance students' enthusiasm for traditional national culture.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that under the guidance of university
authorities, students' societies have become more popular.
</P>
<P>
The problem faced by many universities and colleges this year
is the pressure of unemployment. Officials said that they are
creating opportunities for students to find jobs, while persuading
them to give up out-moded job-seeking attitude.
</P>
<P>
Most universities and colleges have set up complete systems to
provide subsidies and loans for students whose families are
experiencing financial difficulties, Education Ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number Of Drug Addicts Down In Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of drug addicts in
China's Yunnan Province, which borders on the "Golden Triangle",
is down from 57,000 in 1990 to 40,000, which Jiang Pusheng, the
provincial public security department head, attributes to the
combined efforts of special drug teams, a drug publicity campaigns
rehabilitation centers, and halting the cultivation of opium
poppies in the Golden Triangle.
</P>
<P>
The province now has 147 special anti-drug teams, comprising
1,950 police officers and 2,000 other personnel. It spends some
150 million yuan annually on the fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to 1997, the province dealt with 30,000 drug cases
and confiscated more than 25,000 kg of drugs. It has also spent
300 million yuan in recent years helping farmers in areas
bordering northern Myanmar to plant grain and cash crops to
replace opium poppies.
</P>
<P>
It has also had an anti-drug show, published anti-drug books,
and aired special TV programs. It has 85 compulsory rehabilitation
centers and 8 labor rehabilitation centers that attend to some
30,000 drug addicts annually.
</P>
<P>
The Kunming Rehabilitation Center, in a suburb of the
provincial capital, is the largest in eastern and southern
Asia. Zhang Yuzu, its head, says that it has developed a medicine
that helps addicts kick their habit, and now has a cure rate of 20
percent, which is higher than the world average.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
