<HEADLINE> Tibet To Further Boost Private Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet Autonomous
Region plans to create a better environment for the development of
the private economic sector by issuing favorable laws, policies
and regulations, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the autonomous region had 41,000 family
businesses, with a total of 58,000 employees, and 208 private
companies, with over 2,700 employees, up 35.9 percent, 41.9
percent, 20.8 percent and 16.2 percent, respectively, compared
with the figures for the previous year, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the regional administration for industry and
commerce said that the booming private economy has bolstered the
local economy as a whole and brought more job opportunities for
local people.
</P>
<P>
The regional government plans to link the development of the
private sector with the economic development in the region's
agricultural and animal-raising areas. Private companies are
allowed to participate in various kinds of industrial,
agricultural and infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local people, people from other parts of the country
and overseas Tibetans are encouraged to join in the private
sector. Private businessmen will enjoy the same official treatment
as those working in state-owned enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
