<HEADLINE> Uganda's Private Sector, Role Model for Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Building the private sector is the
right way to lead Uganda's economy out of chaos and it has proven
a role model for the rest of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni said this when inaugurating
a 3.5-million-U.S.-Dollar Unilever Soap plant here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"In Africa, Uganda, especially the National Resistance
Movement was the first to be convinced that the private sector is
more efficient ... we are pathfinders," Museveni said. "We are a
role model."
</P>
<P>
"The movement we have set in motion is growing in Africa. The
coming century will be Africa's century. This is because our
markets are still very underexploited," he added, quoted by a
press report.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the president cited the rapid rise of former
Soviet Union through liberalization of economy as an example that
should be followed by all other African countries.
</P>
<P>
In this sense, he said, Uganda has contributed a lot to the
intellectual liberation of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Unilever, a London-based multinational corporation, has a
global turnover of more than 51 billion U.S. Dollars. It
operates in 88 countries and sells its products in more than 150
countries. 
</P>
