<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China City Having Better Luck Dealing with Red Tide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A group has been set up in this
coastal city of east China's Fujian province to monitor the
appearance of the red tide.
</P>
<P>
The group consists of researchers from the Xiamen Environmental
Protection Bureau, the Xiamen environment monitoring center, and
an institute of the China National Oceanic Bureau, among others.
</P>
<P>
Water samples are taken three times a week near Baozhu
Island, the Dayu Sewage Treatment Plant, the beach at Xiamen
University, and Huli Mountain and results are reported to the
media in the hope that fishermen and aquatic farmers can respond
to warning signs.
</P>
<P>
The recent red tide disaster in Fujian and nearby Guangdong in
April gave the local people a bitter lesson. This "Ocean Cancer",
as local fishermen call it, caused by a sudden growth of
microscopic plankton because of weather changes, cuts off the
oxygen supply for shellfish.
</P>
<P>
The red tide can be caused by different types of algae. A small
amount of red tide made up of blue-green algae here last November
proved to be harmless.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen's coastal waters have diverse species of marine life,
all of which help the ecosystem work well, according to Dr. Zhen
Tianling, a member in the China Bureau of International Red Tide
Defense Work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0242 </DOCNO>
