<HEADLINE> Former Boxing Champion Bowe Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Former undisputed heavyweight
champion Riddick Bowe was indicted on Tuesday for allegedly
abducting his estranged wife and their five children.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, a U.S. District Court grand jury charged
him with interstate domestic violence. He faces up to 10 years
in prison and a $250,000 fine if convicted.
</P>
<P>
Judy Bowe and the couple's five children were uninjured in the
alleged abduction on February 25, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Bowe ordered his wife and children into his car and began
driving toward his home. Bowe went some 200 miles before
stopping at a fast food restaurant, where Judy Bowe was able to
get to a telephone and call police.
</P>
<P>
Authorities decided they needed to conduct additional
interviews and consult state police as well as the FBI before
making a decision on whether to arrest Bowe.
</P>
<P>
Bowe retired in 1997, joined the Marine Corps Reserve late
that year to take three months basic training, but he dropped out
11 days later.
</P>
<P>
Bowe was unbeaten in 31 fights and at the top of his game when
he outpointed Evander Holyfield for the undispute heavyweight
championship on November 13, 1992. He lost the WBC title outside
the ring when he refused to fight Lennox Lewis of Britain.
</P>
<P>
He lost the WBA and IBF titles to Holyfield in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
