<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese "Anti-Fake-Goods Hero" Wins Another Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Wang Hai, who has become known as
the "anti-fake-goods hero" for his several-year crusade against
the sale of bogus goods, won another lawsuit recently.
</P>
<P>
But, this time he was not fighting shops that were involved in
selling counterfeit goods, but a company that used his name for an
advertisement that promoted its own products.
</P>
<P>
A newspaper in Chengdu, the capital of southwest China's
Sichuan Province, ran a series of ads in January that said, "Even
the 'Anti-Fake-Goods Hero' Wang Hai couldn't find any fault with
our products", so Wang sued the company, accusing it for having
used his name for commercial purposes without prior consent, and
for damaging his reputation as well.
</P>
<P>
In its final ruling, the Sichuan Provincial Higher Court
concluded that the ads did not hurt Wang's reputation but had
really infringed on his rights in using his name, and ordered the
company to pay 5,000 yuan (some 600 US dollars) in compensatory
damages.
</P>
<P>
This is reported to be one of the first instances in China of a
libel case related to the Advertising Law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
