<HEADLINE> Vietnam Reaches 35 Percent of the Year's Budget Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's state budget balance of
payment recorded total gains in the first five months of this year
equal to 35.3 percent of the projected figure for the whole year,
said a report in the latest issue of the Vietnam Investment Review.
</P>
<P>
State budget gains from foreign-invested companies fell by 3.6
percent during the first five months, while the government did
reap a 2.1 percent increase in tax payments from the state sector.
</P>
<P>
Profits from state-run enterprises met 33.6 percent of the
year's expectations. Profits from the foreign-invested sector were
equivalent to 33.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in tax payments of foreign-invested companies is
based primarily on the reduced price of crude oil, said economists
at the general department of statistics.
</P>
<P>
This means that cash obtained from oil and gas joint ventures
met only 81.1 percent of projected figures, despite an increase of
23.8 percent in crude oil exports.
</P>
<P>
The government gained an increase of some 9 percent in tax
payments from the non-state sector and a 0.8 percent increase from
import and export duties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
