<HEADLINE> OAS Supports Argentina's Sovereignty over Malvinas Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of American States
(OAS) approved a resolution in its 28th general assembly on
Tuesday, supporting Argentina's position on its sovereignty over
the disputed Malvinas (Falkland) Islands.
</P>
<P>
The resolution expressed satisfaction with the reaffirmation of
the Argentine government to "continue exploring all possible
peaceful solutions to the controversy."
</P>
<P>
The OAS also decided to discuss the issue in future meetings
until the dispute is solved.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Argentine Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella told the
third plenary session of the assembly that restoration of the
Malvinas Islands is a long-term goal which cannot be ceded by his
government.
</P>
<P>
Argentina and Britain fought a war over the disputed islands in
1982. It ended with Britain retaining control.
</P>
<P>
The two countries severed their diplomatic relations following
the war, but resumed ties in 1990 following several years of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Britain, however, has never given up its claim to the islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
