<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia, Serb Republic Agree on Refugee Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Croatia and the Bosnian Serb
Republic reached an agreement Tuesday on a the return of refugees
which will be signed within one week.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was clinched Tuesday in talks between Bosnian
Serb Prime Minister Milorad Dodik and Croatian Prime Minister
Zlatko Matesa and Foreign Minister Mate Granic.
</P>
<P>
They focused their talks on the return of refugees, the
implementation of the Dayton peace accord and bilateral relations,
especially economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was based on "a man's right to choose where he
will live and be provided with conditions for a dignified living,"
Matesa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Dodik said the Bosnian Serb Republic supported this approach
which allowed refugees to choose either to return or not.
</P>
<P>
"The Dayton agreement itself said that the rights to return,
compensation, or exchange of property are equal, and we want to
recognize the possibility that people choose one of these three
options," the Bosnian Serb prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that around 50,000 Croatian Serbs took refuge
in the Bosnian Serb entity during Croatia's military operation in
the summer of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Official Croatian data say that more than 71,000 Croats were
expelled from the Serb Republic to Croatia at that time.
</P>
<P>
Next week the Croatian Embassy in Sarajevo will start holding
consular days in the Serb Republic's headquarters in Banja Luka,
where Croatian Serbs will be able to submit their requests for
return.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of heavy international pressure, Croatia recently
adopted a document enabling the unconditional return of Serb
refugees, despite fears that a mass Serb return might destabilize
the country.
</P>
<P>
Matesa told reporters he was very satisfied with his talks with
Dodik and hoped cooperation between Croatia and the Serb Republic
would develop in accordance with mutually acceptable principles.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also discussed issues on economic
cooperation, the establishment of all forms of transport and the
cleaning of the Sava River to make it fit for transport.
</P>
<P>
Croatia and the Bosnian Serb entity are in particular trying to
resume economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Dodik welcomed Croatia's recent revocation of visas for Bosnian
 citizens from the Serb Republic who have new Bosnia-Herzegovina
passports.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed that Bosnian Serb citizens may enter and cross
Croatia without visas and also that the Serb Republic authorities
will guarantee the safety of Croatian citizens crossing its
territory," Dodik said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
