<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Plans Upgrade of 747 Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Boeing, the world's largest
civil airplane producer, has ruled out developing a new super
carrier in favour of upgrading the 747 jet.
</P>
<P>
The market for a new large aircraft was too small to justify
the cost of development, said Joe Ozimek, director of product
marking for the company.
</P>
<P>
He estimated the market demand for bigger planes was fewer than
500, while development costs would reach 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Boeing is now looking at design changes that would allow it to
build less-costly versions of the 747 with more seats and a longer
nonstop flying range.
</P>
<P>
The company has begun offering a stretched version to
airlines. One proposed model, the 747-400Y, would require inserts
to extend the wing length. It would have about 500 seats and fly
over 13,760 km. It is also planning an increased-gross-weight
747-400X that could fly about 14,080 km with 416 seats, according
to Ozimek.
</P>
<P>
But Europe's Airbus Company, which continues with plans for a
550- to 600-seat jetliner to compete with Boeing's 450-seat 747,
expects a market for more than 1,200, and puts development costs
at less than 10 billion dollars, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Other models of Boeing's commercial jets are also being eyed
for upgrades in the next century. Besides the next-generation of
737-600, -700, -800 and -900 now in its order book, Boeing is
looking at a convertible model that could be used to fly
passengers and, with seats removed, carry cargo. A combination
model that carries both passengers and cargo is also a
possibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
