<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bean Output Increases with Imported Technique from US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The northernmost Heilongjiang
Province, China's leading bean producer, has succeeded in raising
the bean output by 20 percent thanks to advanced cultivation
methods imported from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The technology was developed by a bean expert in the State of
Ohio, after the repeated experiments over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Agro-technicians in Heilongjiang further improved the imported
technique in compliance with specific local conditions and
introduced it to five counties on an experimental basis.
</P>
<P>
They adopt rational close planting of short-stock beans at
narrow intervals. And an increased amount of fertilizer and
herbicide were applied to guard against or control insect pests
and eliminate weeds.
</P>
<P>
In this way, the output of beans at the experimental plots is
20 percent higher than that in ordinary fields with the highest
output up 53 percent, said a local agro-technician.
</P>
<P>
To date, the method was spread to 69,000 hectares in 34
counties last year with per-hectare yield of 2572.5 kilograms,
14.4 percent more as compareed with conventional cultivating method.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
