<HEADLINE> Thai Rice Exports Surge in First 5 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's rice exports during the
first five months of this year jumped 49 percent from the same
period last year to 2.79 million tons, a major English newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The value of rice exports rose by 103 percent in baht terms to
38.9 billion baht and 17 percent in dollar terms to 891 million
U.S. dollars compared with that of the same period in 1997, The
Nation said.
</P>
<P>
The exports in May alone amounted to 420,000 tons worth 5.5
billion baht (141 million dollars). Thailand exports an average of
500,000 tons of rice a month.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi as saying Tuesday that importers'
delayed shipments, in particular, to Indonesia and the
Philippines, lowered the growth of rice exports in May.
</P>
<P>
Although the demand for rice in the region has fallen, its
trading in the world market was still high, and is expected to
reach 22.1 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Many countries in the Middle East and Africa started to import
more rice. Japan also opened its domestic rice market under a
commitment to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was eyeing a 27.08 percent share of the total trade,
making it the world's largest rice exporter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Tightens Security in Plantations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has tightened security
in the entire plantation sector following a predawn blast Monday
at Shanon Estate tea factory at Hatton in Central province.
</P>
<P>
A bomb which went off had been placed by two unidentified
youths causing damage to the shifting room of the factory, police
sources here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The entire area was cordoned off and searched by the police
later who asked estate workers to be more vigilant and help
safeguard estate property.
</P>
<P>
The sources said it was obvious that saboteurs wanted to
destabilize the country's main economy, the tea industry, and
cause havoc in the plantation sector.
</P>
<P>
Recently there have been as many as ten blasts of electricity
transformers and telecommunication facilities as well in different
parts of the country, indicating that the saboteurs wanted to
destabilize infrastructure too in the country.
</P>
<P>
As plastic devices had been used in the bombings, police
believe that this sabotage activity was attempted by the Tamil
rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam who have been
engaged in a 15-year war against government troops for a separate
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
