<HEADLINE> Georgian President calls on Russia to Return its Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia should return the military
equipment it has taken from Georgia, Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze told a press conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, Russia took from Georgia a large stock of
military equipment, including aircraft, warships and air defense
systems, the Inter-TASS news agency quoted Shevardnadze as saying.
</P>
<P>
Military experts value the weaponry at 10 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze said Georgia and Russia should find common ground
for the return of the weapons and that a full bilateral
understanding will not only benefit the two countries but also
pose no harm to any other country.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian government has notified the Russian leadership of
the request, the president disclosed. 
</P>
