<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holyfield Ready to Fight Akinwande </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Evander Holyfield said he is
ready to fight Henry Akinwande in the WBA heavyweight boxing title
defense at New York's Madison Square Garden on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"People wonder if I can get up for this fight," Holyfield said
Tuesday at a press conference in New York. "They shouldn't. I'm up
for every fight."
</P>
<P>
Holyfield beat Michael Moorer last November to add the IBF
heavyweight title to the WBA crown he won from Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
Akinwande isn't considered by many to be a tough opponent to
Holyfield despite his imposing height and a 33-1-1 record ruined
only by a defeat to WBC champion Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
"They said the same thing about Holyfield before he fought
Tyson," Akinwande said at Tuesday's final pre-fight press
conference. "I've made a good living proving people wrong in this
sport."
</P>
<P>
Akinwande, by virture of his No. 1 ranking by the WBA, should
not be a hard nut for Holyfield to crack. But with Tyson still
sidelined and his camp unable to make a deal with Lewis for a
title unification, Akinwande is all he has to take.
</P>
<P>
Holyfield will earn some $10 million for the scheduled 12-round
fight. The purse will boost Holyfield's career earnings to some
$185 million.
</P>
<P>
Holyfield has to fight Lewis to unify the heavyweight
championship for the first time since Riddick Bowe threw the WBC
belt into a garbage can after his win over Holyfield in their
first fight.
</P>
<P>
Should Holyfield beat Akinwande, talks could begin again for a
Lewis fight that would probably take place sometime in the
spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
