<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's GDP Growth to Reach 4 Pct in 1999: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's gross domestic
product (GDP) growth could reach four percent next year if its
macroeconomic policies are fine-tuned and implemented with speed,
according to the Pacific Economic Cooperation Council (PECC)'s
annual report for 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
"If confidence returns and there is stability in the currency
markets, there are good prospects for Malaysia's recovery to gain
additional momentum in 1999," the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama reported Wednesday quoting the PECC's Pacific Economic
Outlook (PEO) released in Washington Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The PEO said the growth forecast assumed that macroeconomic
policies are fine-tuned to lessen the negative impact on business,
but the full impact of the devaluation of Malaysia's ringgit, the
wealth effect of the slump in the stock market, credit tightening,
and the fiscal austerity measures introduced last December have
not yet fully worked through the real side of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The PEO anticipated Malaysia's inflation to fall to five
percent and its current account deficit to reach 0.5 percent of
GDP by next year.
</P>
<P>
However, the PEO said, with currency markets still unsettled,
forecasting growth for 1998 and 1999 was problematic.
</P>
<P>
Taking all factors into account, growth is expected to slow to
about 2.0 percent in 1998 when inflation, as measured by the CPI
(consumer price index) would rise to about 7.5 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia's trade surplus is expected to increase and the
services deficit will decrease. The current account deficit in
1998 is anticipated to fall to about one percent of GDP compared
with 5.1 percent of GDP in 1997," the PEO said.
</P>
<P>
"The tight monetary policy stance and fiscal measures
introduced at the end of 1997 will dampen growth in 1998. Lending
to the broad property sector has been curtailed, and credit
growth will fall to 20 percent by the end of the first quarter of
1998, and to 15 percent by the end of 1998," the PEO projected.
</P>
<P>
The report said business closures and retrenchment of workers
would increase the unemployment rate to about five to six percent
from the 2.7 percent level in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, seriously affected by the regional financial crisis,
registered a decline of 1.8 percent in GDP growth in the first
quarter of 1998 as announced by Bank Negara (central bank) last
week.
</P>
<P>
However, the Malaysian government is still hopeful that the GDP
for the whole of 1998 will grow by 2 to 3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Largest Exporter Aiming at High Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, China's
largest exporter, is making new efforts to achieve a 15 percent
growth in export this year.
</P>
<P>
The originally planned export increase was 10 percent, said
Liang Yaowen, deputy director of the provincial Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Commission. However, Guangdong has readjusted
the rate to 15 percent, encouraged by an average rise of 16.1
percent for the first four months.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, the province began to restructure its foreign
trade sector, with greater efforts made to diversify export
markets and to develop ocean trade.
</P>
<P>
The efforts are paying off. During the first four months of the
year, exports to the United States rose by 36.3 percent, Japan,
by 58.9 percent, and European Union, by 22.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The official also attributed the good performance to faster
rebates for export commodities, and this has greatly sped up
exporters' capital turnover.
</P>
<P>
The province is upgrading its labor-intensive exports mix, and
developing high value-added commodities in a bid to compete better
in the world trade market.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis is posing both challenges and
opportunities to the province's foreign trade sector. Relying on
light industrial and textile products for export, similar to
Southeast Asian countries, Guangdong is confronted with importers'
demand for price discounts or deferred payments, Liang said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's exports to Southeast Asian nations dropped by 24.6
percent during the first four months.
</P>
<P>
However, stable economic and political situation in China has
won over some European and American buyers, who had planned to
purchase goods from Southeast Asian countries. And Guangdong,
especially the Pearl River Delta area, is now receiving quite a
number of the returned orders.
</P>
<P>
The province provided more than 40 percent of the country's
total exports in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
