<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Launch First Home-made Satellite in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai people will be able to see in
the sky a "star" of their own as the first Thai-made
micro-satellite is ready for launch later this month.
</P>
<P>
Suchet Chandrarangsa, project manager, was quoted by
Wednesday's Bangkok Post as saying that the satellite was designed
and assembled by Thais, although the parts were imported.
</P>
<P>
The 50-kilogram satellite, called TMSAT, will be launched into
orbit 835 kilometers above earth from Baikanour Cosmodrome in
Kazakhstan on June 23, Suchet said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will serve as a communications and education tool
and supply environmental information on forest conditions, forest
fires, and water and air pollution.
</P>
<P>
TMSAT, worth more than 400 million baht (9.5 million U.S.
dollars), is the brainchild of University of Technology Mahanakhon
in collaboration with Thai Satellite Telecommunication and
Britain's University of Surrey.
</P>
<P>
Under the technology transfer scheme which started two years
ago, 11 university researchers and an engineer were taught how to
design and build a small satellite by Surrey University
scientists.
</P>
<P>
The success may enable Thailand to become the center of
small-scale satellite production in Asia, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The satellite's orbiting course will be over the north-south
axes. It takes one and a half hours to complete an orbit. It will
pass Thailand three times a day for 30 minutes each time.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is expected to last 10 year, Suchet said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Mahanakhon University has an ambitious
plan to build a total of four satellites by 2000, which would make
an integrated telecommunications system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
