<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Prepared to Counter Yangtze Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- This capital of central China's Hubei
Province is going all out to counter possible floods on China's
longest Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Located on the middle reaches of the Yangtze, Wuhan faces the
most serious challenge among China's large cities in countering
floods. The flood season generally runs from May through October.
</P>
<P>
Both the Yangtze and its major affluent Hanshui River run
through Wuhan. In normal years, the floodwater is often two meters
above the surrounding land. In 1954, when an exceptionally severe
flood hit Wuhan, the water level was six m above the land.
</P>
<P>
To counter possible floods this year, Wuhan has launched three
examinations of the embankments along the rivers since last
winter. So far this year, a total of 51 million yuan has been
invested to improve and reinforce the embankments.
</P>
<P>
Soil, stone and sand have been prepared, and radio and alarm
systems have been overhauled in anticipation of flooding,
according to a city official.
</P>
<P>
In addition, buildings totalling more than 7,480 sq m and other
obstacles have been removed to ensure smooth water flow in the
high-water season, he said, adding that flood-control teams are on
high alert.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 52 Tamil Rebels Killed in Fighting in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Over 52 Tamil rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) were killed and over 200
injured during the course of a one-week fierce battle in the north
of Sri Lanka between the rebels and government forces.
</P>
<P>
The casualties among the government troops were 12 soldiers
dead and 25 others injured, security forces sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The fierce fighting took place after the troops resumed their
advance last Wednesday to recapture the strategic Mankulam town on
its way to clear a 75-km supply route between the North and the
South launched in May last year.
</P>
<P>
While the troops were engaged in destroying rebel bunkers
northeast of Mankulam town, the rebels offered stiff resistance
firing mortars and artillery to stop the advancing troops, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Backed by air cover and using heavy artillery and mortars, the
troops were able to destroy six rebel bunkers and advance 1.5
kilometers towards the northeast of Mankulam town Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While the rebel clandestine radio The Voice of the Tigers
announced they had lost 39 cadres with 150 more injured, the
security sources said that the troops would continue their advance
as they had been able to foil the stratagem adopted by the rebels.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
