<HEADLINE> Jordan's Future Still Undecided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan, who is going to
play against the Utah Jazz in the first game of the NBA Finals on
Wednesday, said another championship or a loss won't be a
determining factor to his future.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of the season, it's about evaluating where the
organization is and some of the decisions they have to think
through and base my decision on that," Jordan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
For most of the season, Jordan has staked his future to the
return of coach Phil Jackson, who has declared he will quit the
position.
</P>
<P>
Scottie Pippen, one of the Bulls' leading scorer who will be a
free agent next year, has openly said he will make a leave after
this season.
</P>
<P>
Jackson has used a phrase of "Last Dance 98" to describe the
team's final season together.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls chairman Jerry Reinsdorf said last month he would be
inclined to bring back all the team's major players should the
Bulls win their sixth championship and that he would give Jordan
ample time to make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
But Jordan insisted Tuesday that a win or a loss against the
Utah in the finals won't determine his future.
</P>
<P>
"I've lost at the end of the season before and continued to
play and won at the end of the season and continued to play,"
Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
"If my hunger and my excitement for the game still continue and
I have the appetite for that at the end of the season, I will
continue to play," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
