<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuerten Disqualified from Doubles at French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil was
disqualified from the doubles match at the French Open here on
Tuesday for his misconduct at the court.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten, last year men's singles champion here who played with
fellow Fernando Meligeni, threw his racket which just missed
umpire Bruno Rebeuh after he lost the first set tiebreak in his
quarter-final against Australia's Pat Rafter and Sweden's Jonas
Bjorkman.
</P>
<P>
Rebeuh immediately awarded the match to sixth-seeded pair
Rafter and Bjorkman.
</P>
<P>
Tournament referee Gilbert Ysern confirmed that 21-year-old
Kuerten has been disqualified from the tournament for
"unsportsmanlike conduct" and would be fined.
</P>
<P>
Ysern said there was a possibility Kuerten could be banned from
his next Grand Slam event.
</P>
<P>
Rafter and Bjorkman now play Dutch top seeds Jacco Eltingh and
Paul Haarhuis.
</P>
<P>
Third-seeded Mahesh Bhupathi and Leander Paes of India will
play Canada's Daniel Nestor and Mark Knowles of the Bahamas in the
other semi-final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
