<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Nordic Paper Industry Giants Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Two Nordic paper industry giants,
Sweden's Stora and Finland's Enso, on Tuesday announced a plan to
merge and become the world's biggest newsprint and paper producer.
</P>
<P>
The merger would create the biggest forest processing group
in Europe as well as the world's largest producer of paper board.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish government, which owns 44 percent of Enso, approved
the merger Tuesday and will ask the Finnish parliament for final
clearance.
</P>
<P>
Stora's market capitalization is about five billion
U.S. dollars and Enso's about three billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two Nordic companies had sales of about 1.5 billion dollars
each in the first quarter of the year. Their combined 1997 sales
were 11 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The new company, to be named Stora Enso, has a workforce of
about 40,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Enso's chief executive Jukka Haermaelae will be the CEO of the
new company and Stora's CEO Bjoern Haegglund will be the group's
deputy chief executive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
