<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Government Prepares Economic Adjustments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The new government of Costa Rica
will adopt a series of economic measures this year in an effort to
trim tax deficit, a senior official of the Finance Ministry said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Costa Rica's tax deficit this year was forecast
at about 4.8 percent, much higher than the previously expected 3.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The official refused to reveal details of the plan, but he said
some measures were ruled out, including a minor salary adjustment
for public sector workers in the middle of the year, and a small
rise in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica is expected to achieve an economic growth rate of
five percent this year, but some pressures have arisen affecting
the tax deficit and increasing the trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
President Miguel Angel Rodriguez, an economist, has repeatedly
expressed his concern over the tax deficit.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped to end state monopoly system in some sectors such
as telecommunications and insurance, and to privatize some public
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
