<HEADLINE> Castro Meets U.S. Religious Representatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Fidel Castro, president of Cuba's
Council of State, met a delegation from the United States National
Council of Christian Churches on Monday led by General Secretary
Joan Campbell.
</P>
<P>
He discussed the history and life of churches in the United
States and Cuba with the delegation.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the current situation in Cuba and the
problems it is facing, as well as the U.S. policy on the embargo
against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. religious delegation, invited by the Cuban Council of
Churches, arrived here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the delegation will visit temples and health
centers in Havana.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, Campbell said the delegation's visit to the
Caribbean island was positive. She also rejected the proposed
humanitarian aid project to Cuba sponsored by U.S. Senator Jesse
Helms.
</P>
<P>
The United States National Council of Christian Churches groups
34 churches, including Protestant, Orthodox and Afro-American
churches with nearly 52 million members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
