<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank To Raise Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand is prepared to
raise short-term interest rates to support the baht, Bank Governor
Chatumongol Sonakul has announced.
</P>
<P>
The bank will increase interest rates through the bond
repurchase market to deter speculation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol made the announcement Tuesday following the
depreciation of the baht in the past few days, Bangkok Post
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The baht, which has ranged between 38 and 40 to the U.S. dollar
over the past few months, has fallen steadily in the past few days
amid increasing investor concern about the economic prospects for
the region.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trade Tuesday, the baht stood at 42.10/20 to
the U.S. dollar, against 41.85/95 one day earlier.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said higher interest rates would theoretically help
spur demand for the baht as investors switched funds from foreign
exchange to enjoy higher margins in the repurchase market.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said higher interest rates were only a temporary
measure which would be eased once the baht stabilized.
</P>
<P>
He said regulators would intervene to ease volatility in
exchange rates, but would allow market forces to set rates and not
try to reverse trends.
</P>
<P>
A further depreciation of the baht would spur inflation and
worsen the debt burden of local corporations with foreign currency
exposure.
</P>
<P>
"The concern now is not that inflation will rise, but that the
recession will deepen. Even so, the central bank cannot lower
interest rates while foreign exchange rates remain a concern,"
Chatumongol said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
