<HEADLINE> Strikes in Hospitals in Nicaragua Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Ninety percent of Nicaraguan
hospitals have stopped their operations after another 14,000
health workers went on strike from Monday, Radio Pensamiento of
Managua reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Health Workers has called an indefinite
strike to demand better salaries, job reclassifications, labor
stability and re-hiring of all their fired colleagues.
</P>
<P>
This indefinite strike has aggravated the crisis of the health
system just before the onset of winter and as outbreaks of malaria
and dengue are expected.
</P>
<P>
Three and a half weeks ago, the physicians formed a labor union
and began to hold strikes to demand a salary increase of 200
percent.
</P>
<P>
Strikers said that only emergencies will be treated before the
government responds to their demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
