 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The second training class on Deng Xiaoping Theory and the
guidelines laid down by the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) for members and alternate members
of the CPC Central Committee closed here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
At the closing ceremony, Chinese President Jiang Zemin, who is
also general secretary of the CPC Central Committee, called on
Party members to overcome all difficulties and score new victories
with the correct guidance of Deng Xiaoping Theory.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin met here yesterday afternoon with
Samuel Berger, assistant to the U.S. president for national
security affairs.
</P>
<P>
Jiang conferred with Berger on Sino-U.S. relations and matters
related to U.S. President Bill Clinton's upcoming state visit to
China. Berger told Jiang that President Clinton is looking forward
to his visit to China.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the Chinese National People's Congress
(NPC) Standing Committee, met with former Romanian President Ion
Iliescu and his party yesterday. Li said China values its ties
with Romania and is ready to foster a comprehensive Sino-Romanian
relationship of friendly cooperation oriented with the next
century.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji met yesterday with visiting
Belarussian Defense Minister General Alexander Chumakov, who
arrived in China for the first time on May 30.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China will not support, encourage or engage in nuclear
proliferation and will not help other nations develop nuclear
weapons, said Zhu Bangzao yesterday during a regular news briefing
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- China is ready to open its huge state-owned rail
transportation sector to domestic and foreign investors, said
Railways Minister Fu Zhihuan yesterday during a news conference in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- Construction of China's first high-speed railway linking
Beijing and shanghai will begin in year 2000, according to Shen
Zhijie, director of the high-speed railway pre-feasibility study
office under the Ministry of Railways.  
</P>
