<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Space Shuttle Discovery Launched Into Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle Discovery was
sent into space Tuesday evening from Kennedy Space Center, Cape
Canaveral,Flo., carrying with it six crew members and the Alpha
Magnetic Spectrometer designed and made by scientists from China,
the United States and other countries.
</P>
<P>
During its 10-day space trip, the space shuttle will for the
first time place the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer, a 3.5 ton
particle detector, into space and carry out high energy physics
experiments.
</P>
<P>
The particle detector consists of five major elements: a
permanent magnet, the critical part of the detector made by the
Chinese Science Academy; time-of-flight scintillators; a silicon
microstrip tracker; anti-coincidence counters also made by Chinese
scientists; and the aerogel threshold Cerenkov counter.
</P>
<P>
The Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer experiments aim to answer two
questions in high energy physicis: first, if equal amounts of
matter and antimatter were produced at the beginning of the
universe as described by the Big Bang scenario, and the galaxies
we now see are made only of matter, where has the antimatter gone?
second, since the mass of a galaxy seems to be greater than the
visible mass of all its stars, gas and dust, is there dark matter
of a new kind that has eluded discovery?
</P>
<P>
The Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer experiments are an
international cooperation led by American-Chinese scientist and
1976 Nobel Prize winner Dr. Ding, and participated by scientists
from 37 research institutions in China, the United States, Russia,
France, Italy and others.
</P>
<P>
Discovery will dock with the Russian "Mir" space station and
take back the U.S. astronaut Andrew Thomas who has worked almost
six months on the Mir station. This is the ninth and the last
docking for U.S. space shuttle with the Russian Mir station.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. space shuttle will return to the ground on June 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Takes Measures to Punish World Cup Hooligans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) - Britain has reached an agreement with
France which forbids British soccer fans who cause trouble at this
year's World Cup to return to France for the rest of the
tournament, Home Secretary Jack Straw announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Straw told a news conference that under the deal with France,
any British hooligan convicted of a soccer related offence at the
World Cup could face court action at home on their return in
addition to any punishment handed down by the French judiciary.
</P>
<P>
He said that English and Welsh courts could impose restriction
orders on top of punishment imposed in France.
</P>
<P>
"I have sought to ensure that we do everything we can help to
ensure that those who are decent and law-abiding are able to watch
football in safety and comfort," Straw said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that last year, Straw had encouraged judges to
use restriction orders when convicting anyone of a soccer-related
crime as one of the measures to prevent UK fans from causing
trouble.
</P>
<P>
At present 65 British soccer troublemakers have been imposed
restriction orders to prevent them from attending the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Straw said that he expected the number of orders to increase
before the World Cup begins on June 10 in France as many cases of
soccer violence are still underway in courts and some other
troublemakers may be arrested at other matches before then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
