<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan May Develop Nuclear Warheads Soon: U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
that India and Pakistan could develop nuclear warheads for
medium-range missiles within one or two years.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon, in response to questions about
missiles being developed by India and Pakistan to carry nuclear
warheads, said, "Our best guess is that it would probably take
them a year or two to weaponize... by putting them onto warheads."
</P>
<P>
"Of course, that can depend a lot on how much they decide to
test, what the state of their current program is now, how much
security they want about whether it works," he added. "So there
are many, many variables."
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the United States was urging the two countries not
to "miniaturize" nuclear devices recently tested by India and
Pakistan so that they could be mounted on missiles to threaten
each other.
</P>
<P>
"One of the things we're appealing to both countries to do is
not to weaponize their nuclear warheads," he told reporters. "We
would like them to stop testing. We would like them to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. We would like them to sign the
fissile materials agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bacon described the situation in South Asia as "extremely
dangerous and volatile" because of the face-off between two
antagonists. "We are very, very concerned about the possibility of
miscalculation."
</P>
<P>
But Bacon would not call the situation "a hair-trigger stance."
He said the steps taken by India and Pakistan in the wake of their
tests had been mostly defensive in nature and skirmishing around
disputed Kashmir "is pretty much a fact of life." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980603.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Health Modernization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday approved
an interest-free credit equivalent to 24 million U.S. dollars for
an adaptable program loan to help finance the health sector
modernization program of the Nicaraguan government.
</P>
<P>
The health sector management program, of which this project is
the first phase, will improve the efficiency, effectiveness, and
equity of the Nicaraguan health system.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to implement sector reforms and targeted
investments over a period of nine years from 1998 to 2007 through
a phased approach, gradually and geographically expanding some
program activities to the whole country while deepening and
consolidating others.
</P>
<P>
The first phase from 1998-2002 will focus on developing pilot
sector reforms and priority programs and on building the
experience, knowledge, and capacity to expand them during the
second phase. The second phase will cover the period 2002-2007 and
will support full implementation and consolidation of the program.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the first phase is estimated at 32 million
dollars. The World Bank's credit, which will finance 75 percent of
the total cost, will come from the International Development
Association, the Bank's concessional lending wing for developing
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
