<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Falls Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the
Japanese yen Tuesday as traders speculated that major
industrialized nations will jointly intervene to help Japan prop
up the yen.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 138.83 yen,
down from 139.70 yen late Monday. The dollar also was changing
hands at 1.7806 marks, up from 1.7781.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's fell against the yen on an unconfirmed report by a
Japanese newspaper that senior G-7 officials will meet to discuss
yen weakness and Russia's economic crisis. Traders feared the
meeting would lead to joint intervention knocking down the U.S.
currency.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday:
1.4808 Swiss francs, up from 1.4758; 5.9735 French francs, up from
5.9615; 1,755.00 Italian lire, up from 1,751.00; and 1.4528
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4580.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6393 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6407 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
