<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek-Albanian Undersea Tunnel to Be Open in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- An undersea tunnel linking up
western Greece and neighboring Albania will be open to traffic in
October 1999.
</P>
<P>
Around 75 percent of the Aktio-Preveza link has been built and
the 28 billion drachma (about 90 million U.S. dollar) project is
keeping within its time scale, Greece's Public Works Minister
Costas Laliotis said at a ceremony to launch the project's second
phase.
</P>
<P>
He said that detailed engineering for the project cost 8
billion drachmas (about 26 million dollars) and the project would
be proposed for funding under the European Union's third community
support framework.
</P>
<P>
The project's entire stretch has a total length of 4,710
meters, comprising an undersea tunnel of 1,570 meters with an
internal width of 10.6 meters and height of 6.40 meters.
</P>
<P>
The tunnel will have two lanes for traffic with a total width
of eight meters and walkways on either side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
